<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Calls for Financial Rectification  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Commercial banks should establish a self-restraint mechanism
and a mechanism for guarding against risks," he urged.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of commercial banks found speculating in stocks on
credit or doing extra-account business will be removed from the
the post, Zhu warned.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a political and ideological education and
professional training among bank employees.
</P>
<P>
Local governments and departments must not intervene in the
business of banks or approve the establishment of financial
institutions without authorization, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Through the joint efforts of various sides, financial risks
can be prevented and warded off and the financial industry can
develop steadily, making a greater contribution to national
economic and social development," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
In a group discussion with deputies from the Tibetan Autonomous
Region, the Vice-Premier said that it is a reliable guarantee for
the Tibet's long-term stability and prosperity to maintain in the
region political stability, economic development, unity among
ethnical groups and social progress.
</P>
<P>
It is also a big issue that concerns the safeguarding of
national safety and stability, as well as the overall situation of
modernization, he said.
</P>
<P>
He commended the region for achieving an economic growth rate
of over 10 percent for two years in a row and reporting a good
agricultural harvest for nine consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
The Party Central Committee and the State Council are very
concerned about the development of Tibet, tilting more toward the
region and other areas inhabited by ethnic minorities in transfer
payment and in the arrangement of key construction projects, Zhu
said.
</P>
<P>
"Though there are difficulties in the economic work of Tibet,
</P>
<P>
... we certainly can achieve sustained economic growth and
social stability in Tibet by relying on people of various ethnic
groups and bringing into full play the initiative of officials at
all levels and people of all communities," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
