<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhu Rongji Calls for Financial Rectification  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said
today that the government will bolster its effort to rectify the
country's financial order and urged commercial banks to cut
non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
In a group discussion with deputies to the Eighth National
People's Congress from eastern Fujian Province, Zhu said that the
banking sector must make a greater effort to rectify the financial
order and prevent financial risks, in order to cut the ratio of
the banks' non-performing loans by two percent annually in the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
"If a bank cannot meet this requirement, its president will be
held accountable," said Zhu, who is a member of the Standing
Committee of the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector has over the years played an important
role in promoting national economic development and in maintaining
social stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, we must be sober-minded and recognize existing
problems," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The problem of delayed repayment of bank loans and interest is
fairly serious, he said. Some state-owned enterprises and a fairly
large number of key construction projects begin to suffer losses
and are forced out of production soon after they go into
operation, increasing the amount of bad assets of banks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some non-banking financial institutions are very poor in terms
of asset quality and are exposed to great financial risks for
violating business rules, raising funds illegally, extending
loans at high interest rates, the vice-premier said.
</P>
<P>
If proper measures are taken from right now, risks can be
prevented and warded off, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the central bank, the People's Bank of China, will
this year regard financial supervision as the most important part
of its work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
