<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Macao Businesspeople Welcome to Join "Glorious Cause" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Entrepreneurs from Hong Kong and
Macao are welcome to join the "Glorious Cause" in the interior
areas, which are aimed to expand their business operations into
the central and western areas to help eliminate poverty there.
</P>
<P>
Hu Deping, a National Committee member of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) and vice-chairman of the
All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce, made the call at a
press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
The "Glorious Cause" was launched by 10 entrepreneurs from the
private economic sector in April, 1994, who focused on alleviating
poverty through investments and setting up factories in central
and western areas of China.
</P>
<P>
Hu, also vice-president of the China Association for the
Promotion of the Glorious Cause, noted that his association will
provide services of information, introduction of investment
environment and coordination for Hong Kong and Macao partners as
well as businesspeople in China's inerior areas.
</P>
<P>
Some Hong Kong and Macao business people have already joined
thiNevertheless, the Cause and made contributions, according to him.
</P>
<P>
But he said that his association will not establish a branch
office in Hong Kong according to the relevant rules.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 4,000 individual businesspeople have devoted
themselves to this "Glorious Cause" project, which has invested a
total of three billion yuan to start 820 projects in
poverty-stricken areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advisors Speak on Various Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Seven members of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, the country's top advisory body, delivered speeches at
a plenary meeting, covering topics ranging from state-owned
enterprise reform, the return of Hong Kong to employment and
poverty relief.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Siwei, president of the Central Committee of China
Democratic National Construction Association, focused on deepening
reform of the economic system.
</P>
<P>
The speech of Wang Yuezhao, executive vice chairman of the
CPPCC National Committee's Subcommittee on the Economy, was about
improving the economic efficiency of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Tsui Tsin tong, a member from Hong Kong, said that the
advantages of Hong Kong as an international economic metropolis
must be safeguarded.
</P>
<P>
Member Jing Shuping called for greater effort to mobilize
the forces of all communities and create more job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting lasted two hours. Another 29 members will
speak at the advisory body's plenary meetings through March 8.
</P>
<P>
By nine this morning, CPPCC members had sent in 349 written
speeches, the most in the history of the advisory body, which
is in its fifth session here.
</P>
<P>
The final number is expected to reach 400, compared with 340
for the previous session last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
