<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Fail Canadians on Environment Issues, Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Canadians have given federal and
provincial governments failing grades for their handling of
environmental issues, a recent poll suggests.
</P>
<P>
The federal government got an average rating of 4.8 when
Canadians were asked to mark its overall performance on
environmental issues on a scale of one to 10. The provinces earned
an average rating of 4.7.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted by Insight Canada Research in November for
Environment Canada, is considered accurate within 2.9 percentage
points 19 times out of 20, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that nine out of 10 Canadians were troubled by
the state of the environment, and most expressed serious concerns
about the potential damage brought by global warming.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent said they were concerned about climate change
and the damage it could do to the lakes and forests of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The majority (86 percent) of Canadians polled said they were
concerned about the fact that Canada will not meet its
international commitment to reduce greenhouse gases to 1990 levels
by 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Communist Party Figure On Economic Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The deepening of economic
restructuring should start with reform of the economic system,
putting an end to the practice of giving priority to local
interests and reducing redundant construction.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Siwei, Chairman of the Central Committee of the China
Democratic National Construction Association (CDNCA), made a
speech on further economic restructuring at the second plenary
meeting of the Fifth Session of the Eighth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference today, on
behalf of the CDNCA.
</P>
<P>
He suggested the establishment of a mechanism in the country's
investment system to minimize investment risks; establishment and
development of a capital market; and increase of macroeconomic
controls.
</P>
<P>
He said that reform of government departments and change of
government functions should be made to separate the functions of
the government and the enterprise.
</P>
<P>
And the managerial mechanism of state-owned enterprises should
be altered and their economic structure adjusted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
