<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicle Sales in Canada Up 10.5 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Vehicle sales in Canada climbed
10.5 percent in February, with Japanese brands leading the way and
nearly all automaker reported gains.
</P>
<P>
Canada's overall auto sales last month rose to 87,285 from
79,315 a year earlier. It's the sixth straight month of sales
increases.
</P>
<P>
The momentum suggests that optimistic industry forecasts --
five percent or more gains this year -- may prove true, reports
said today.
</P>
<P>
In February, Ford Canada sold 20,593 vehicles, 17.1 percent
more over the same month last year. It saw a 32.5 percent increase
in minivans, pickups and sport-utility vehicles, and 4.8 percent
decline in car sales.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler Canada sales rose 0.2 percent to 15,546. Its car sales
drop 12.2 percent, while minivans, pickups and sport-utility
vehicles rose 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
General Motors Canada is the only one of the Big Three North
American auto makers that reported a sales decline last month. Its
overall sales dropped 7.0 percent to 27,328.
</P>
<P>
The resurgence of Japanese models continued, the reports said.
Japanese automaker sales soared 49 percent from February 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
