<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford's Car Sales in US Market Down in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Ford Motor Co., the No. 2
largest auto maker in the U.S., saw a decline of 3 percent in its
sales last month comparing with strong year-earlier results.
</P>
<P>
Ford's passenger-car sales fell by 8.5 percent as U.S.
consumers continued to flock to light trucks and as it struggled
to compete against foreign auto makers, The Wall Street Journal
reported today.
</P>
<P>
But Ford's light truck sales rose by 1.5 percent despite tight
inventories of the hot-selling, full-size Expedition sport-utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The GM and Chrysler announced Monday that their U.S. sales last
month were also down by 7.5 percent and 3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Big Three's sales declines, overall auto sales in
the U.S. remained robust last month, particularly comparing with
strong results in February of 1966.
</P>
<P>
Sales of cars and light trucks in February totaled 1,153,827,
0.9 percent less than the sales of 1,212,495 a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Japanese auto makers are continuing to grab market share from
the U.S. Big Three auto makers.
</P>
<P>
Toyota Motor Corp. posted a 17 percent increase in U.S. light
vehicle sales last month while Honda's sale gained by 9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
