<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Defends Housing Project in E. Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu said here today that the much-criticized housing project
in East Jerusalem is a "most natural" decision which would
accommodate both the Jewish and Arab needs for housing.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the project in Har Homa has actually been
"overblown," Netanyahu complained at a joint press conference held
with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak following their two-hour
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu arrived here earlier today, exactly a week after Israel
decided to build 6,500 Jewish homes in Har Homa, a tree-covered
hill in East Jerusalem, taken by Israel in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, trying to downplay the negative side, said
that there is no other way to give much-needed homes to residents,
both Arab and Jewish, in the city, but to build new houses for
them.
</P>
<P>
"They have nowhere else to go... Jerusalem is a living city and
it has to expand," he said, adding that Israel has devoted 50
million U.S. dollars for building infrastructures in Arab East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He noted that along with the 2,500 Jewish homes, Israel also
decided to build 3,000 houses for Arabs and 70 percent of the Har
Homa project is "private Jewish land."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said it would be the first new settlement in
Jerusalem, where Israel wants to have as their "eternal and
indivisible" capital. The former Israeli Labor government, under
pressure, had decided to postpone any decision on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Mubarak publicly disagreed over whether peace
agreements between Israel and Palestine block Israel from building
new homes for Jews in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Though the Israeli leader denied that Oslo agreements forbid
such buildings in Jerusalem, Mubarak chipped in to say the fifth
article of Oslo provided that any decision on the holy city should
be put off until the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, apparently had failed to convince the Israeli leader
of the "complications of the peace process in the future," warned
that the Har Homa issue is likely to put the "final status" talks,
due to start within a few weeks, in doubt.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders looked tense and even angry on occasions during
the 30-minute news conference here.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president said his talks with Netanyahu also dwelt
with what should be done and voiced his belief that Jerusalem issue
is sensitive, but could be solved.
</P>
<P>
"we are resolved to exert further efforts in order to move
ahead," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Arrested for Murder of Hun Sen's Relative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Three men have been arrested
and charged with the murder of Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun
Sen's brother-in-law, police official said at a press conference
today.
</P>
<P>
Mok Chito, chief of the Phnom Penh municipal criminal police,
named the three suspects as Suos Kasem, 26, Prum Meanrith, 37, and
Srun Vong Vannak, the 30-year-old security chief of the Khmer
Nation Party led by former Finance Minister Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
Mok Chito said Vannak promised 50,000 U.S. dollars to Suos
Kasem if the latter could kill Kov Samuth, deputy director of the
Interior Ministry's economic department whose wife is the sister
of Hun Sen's wife.
</P>
<P>
According to Mok Chito, Suos Kasem accepted the deal and was
offered 2,000 dollars, a motorbike, a pistol and a magazine of
cartridge at a place near Wat Phnom. The three followed Kov Samuth
three times in 10 days before Suos Kasem shot and killed Kov
Samuth and escaped to Tralok Bek, Tuol Kork.
</P>
<P>
Kov Samuth exited a Phnom Penh restaurant in the morning of
November 19, 1996, when a waiting assassin shot him six times.
</P>
<P>
Suos Kasem returned later to Phnom Penh and went to the KNP
office in a bid to meet Vannak for the rest of the reward for the
murder, and after being told Vannak was not in the office, he went
first for hiding in Poipet and moved to other places afterwards,
Mok Chito said.
</P>
<P>
Suos was quoted as saying that "after learning Hun Sen's
declaration that the murderer would be accorded lenient treatment
if he exposed the man behind the murder, I decided to hand in
myself to the police."
</P>
<P>
Mok Chito said following Suos Kasem's confession, the police
investigated his statement and arrested Srun Vong Vannak on
February 14 and Prum Meanrith on February 17 after concluding that
Suos is the real killer who shot dead Kov Samuth.
</P>
<P>
Mok Chito said the court issued warrants to arrest Vannak and
Meanrith and charged three with deliberately planning the killing.
</P>
<P>
Mok Chito attributed the delay in making public the case to the
detainees' demand for secrecy and safety and said the police are
searching the man behind the murder as they do not not believe
such man as Vannak has an amount of money as large as 50,000
dollars to pay for Suos Kasem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> August First Rockets, Shandong Bulls in Semifinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion August First
Rockets took an easy win of 110-89 over Shenyang Lions Wednesday
in the second leg of quarterfinals of the Chinese basketball first
division league, booking a berth in the semifinals which starts on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yudong and Zhang Tao each hit 22 points to lead the Rockets
for the second win in the home-and-away quarterfinals over the
Lions, which losing by 50-points in their first encounter four
day's ago.
</P>
<P>
In Sunday's semifinals, the August First Rockets, seeking their
third consecutive title, is facing Guangdong Tigers, a 87-82
winners over Shanghai Orientals later on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the other semifinals, Shandong Fleming Bulls will takes on
Liaoning Hunters to decide the other finals spot.
</P>
<P>
Gang Xiaobin scored 24 points and grabbed a season high 19
rebounds for Shandong Bulls, who had to overcame a slow star and
rallied from 13 points behind to beat Jiangsu Nangang 77-74.
</P>
<P>
In their first meet last Sunday, Shandong routed Jiangsu 104-72
when Jiangsu lost their league scoring title winner Hu Weidong
with a foot injury midway in the first half.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning played a balanced game to beat Lianhuang for the
second time in a week. The Liaoning Hunters outrebounded the
Lianhang Eagles 36-27.
</P>
<P>
The winners of the two home-and-away semifinals will enter in
the finals of the 12-team league. 
</P>
</TEXT>
