<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Defends Housing Project in E. Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Viewed as an Israeli bid to
tighten grip on the third holiest city of Islam, the Har Homa plan
already sparked wide-spread Palestinian demonstrations and
worldwide criticism.
</P>
<P>
In case that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat makes good on his
threat to declare the Palestinian state if Israel goes on with the
plan, Mubarak said that Egypt would consult with "Arab brothers"
in the Arab League and comes up with a decision.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu also pledged his commitment to the U.N. Security
resolutions 224 and 338 as the base for future talks, despite what
he termed as "different interpretations" with Arabs.
</P>
<P>
"We stress commitment to go ahead on the peace road with the
Palestinians and other parties in the Arab world," he said.
</P>
<P>
Nine months into office, Netanyahu said Israel has fulfilled
several obligations under the Hebron agreement, such as release of
Palestinian woman prisoners, ease of closure on the West Bank and
Gaza as well as financial transference to the Palestinian
Authority in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
On economic cooperation, Mubarak denied that he has imposed
restrictions on Egyptian businessmen to do business with the
Israeli side, but implied that the peace prospect has its impact.
</P>
<P>
Besides Jerusalem, the talks between Mubarak and Netanyahu also
dealt with the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, frozen for 12
months. Mubarak was expected to urge Netanyahu to come up with a
new formula to persuade Syria to return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
But he gave no details and only said he would discuss these
proposals and ideas during talks in Washington with U.S. President
Bill Clinton on March 10.
</P>
<P>
This is Netanyahu's second visit to Egypt since he assumed
office last June. Since then, Mubarak has conditioned inviting the
Israeli leader to Cairo on progress on the Palestinian-Israeli
talks on the long-delayed Israeli partial pullback from the West
Bank town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed the Hebron withdrawal under the January 15
agreement with the Palestinian National Authority. It is committed
to starting the first stage of redeployment in rural areas of the
West Bank before March 7, a date Israel very likely to delay
because of Har Homa.
</P>
<P>
The meeting with Netanyahu precedes Mubarak's March 10 trip to
Washington, which would also deal with the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a key mediator in the peace process, is the first Arab
country to make peace with Israel, in 1979, but ties remain cool
between them.
</P>
<P>
At a time, Israel accused Egypt of hamstringing the
Palestinians on reaching the Hebron agreement and tried to exclude
Egypt from mediation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
