<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's '97 Budget Clears Lower House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Japan's fiscal 1997 budget was
passed by the 500-member House of Representatives today with the
backing of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party and its two
parliamentary allies -- the Social Democratic Party and New Party
Sakigake.
</P>
<P>
The passage of the 77.39 trillion yen (645 billion
U.S. dollars) budget, the biggest ever in Japan, paved the way for
its effective enactment by the end of the current fiscal year
without the need for a stopgap budget.
</P>
<P>
The general account budget of fiscal 1997, which goes from
April this year to March 1998, is three percent bigger than the
initial budget for fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
The planned rise in consumption tax from 3 to 5 percent in
fiscal 1997 and the abolition of special tax breaks will generate
an additional 5 trillion yen (42 billion dollars) in the revenue.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to issue 16.71 trillion yen (139
billion dollars) in bonds to help finance the expenditure, a fifth
less than the amount raised through bonds in fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
General expenditure is set at 43.81 trillion yen (365 billion
dollars), with 4.95 trillion yen (41 billion dollars) going to
defense, 1.17 trillion yen (10 billion dollars) to official
development assistance, 9.74 trillion yen (81 billion dollars) to
public works projects and 14.55 trillion yen (121 billion dollars)
for social security costs.
</P>
<P>
The budget also includes obligations such as servicing the
national debt, 16.8 trillion yen (140 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The budget, which has been sent to the upper house for debate,
is certain to become law at midnight on April 3 even if the upper
house fails to act by then, because the Japanese Constitution
stipulates that the budget is automatically enacted 30 days after
the lower house passes it and sends it to the House of
Councillors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
