<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latest German GDP Data Shows Economic Stagnation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economy stagnated at the
end of last year, as GDP figures for the final quarter showed
virtually no change from the third quarter, federal authorities
said today.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product in the third quarter of 1996 was 2.3
percent higher than in the same period in 1995, and GDP as a whole
for 1996 grew by 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The silver lining was a 4.1 percent growth in capital
investment in the final quarter, although the rise for 1996 as a
whole was 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest data supported the pessimistic outlook by economic
institutes for the country's economy in early 1997. The
Berlin-based DIW Economic Research Institute claimed Germany's
GDP might fall 0.25 percent in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Economics Guenter Rexrodt said the stagnation at
the end of 1996 was "by no means a new weakness in growth", and
stuck to the government's projection of 2.5 percent GDP growth for
1997.
</P>
<P>
But some less optimistic experts have pointed out a lack of
stimulus for the German economy, citing a slowdown in the
construction sector, weak consumer demand and moderate growth in
public spending. They noted that economic performance now rests
solely on exports, which hit a record 784.3 billion marks (461
billion U.S. dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Official data manifested a 1.4 percent decline in government
spending in the fourth quarter last year on an annualised basis, even
though as a whole in 1996, an increase of 2.4 percent was
registered.
</P>
<P>
Analysts expected a halt in growth in public spending this year
in view of the government's bid to trim social welfare and to keep
budget within the limits required for the launch of the EU single
currency.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption was up slightly by 1.3 percent in 1996, but
that was seen as inadequate to boost economy this year taking
declining real income into account. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
