<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cabinet Reshuffle Can't Save Ukraine's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 5 (Xinhua) -- President Leonid Kuchma's cabinet
reshuffle on February 25 isn't enough to save Ukraine's ailing
economy, a Ukrainian lawmaker said here today.
</P>
<P>
Parliament Deputy Yuri Buzdugan said the shake-up of the
government could not accelerate economic reforms, because
President Leonid Kuchma was likely to fill influential positions
not with experts, but with people loyal to him.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma dismissed four ministers on February 25 amid growing
concerns about the performance of the Ukrainian economy.
</P>
<P>
He fired Finance Minister Valentin Koronevski, Economics
Minister Vasil Gureyev, Statistics Minister Alexander Osaulenko and
Valeri Malev, Minister of Machine Building, Military-Industrial
Complex and Conversion.
</P>
<P>
Koronevski and Osaulenko were sacked for their poor performance
while the dismissals of Gureyev and Malev were explained by their
transfer to other work. But the state-run Ukrainian Television
News said the depressing state of the country's economy was the
reason behind the reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
At a closed-door cabinet meeting on February 21, Ukrainian
Prime Minister Pavel Lazarenko attacked the four dismissed
ministers by name and also criticized the work of the Ministry of
Industry, the Ministry of the Coal Industry, the State Committee
for the Food Industry and the State Oil and Gas Committee.
</P>
<P>
The dismissals must now be followed by wholesale reform of the
Finance Ministry and the Economics Ministry, said a Western
economics adviser to the government who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
He complained that the two ministries were full of old
bureaucrats with a Soviet mentality. He said, "They don't have the
vaguest idea about the role of these ministries in a free-market
economy."
</P>
<P>
At the February 21 meeting, Lazarenko blamed the Finance
Minister Valentin Koronevski for the banking system's inability to
satisfy even the short-term credit needs of the economy. Credit
has dried up as Ukraine has restricted money supply to rein in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also complained that the government did not
have a clear picture of economic conditions. "Data from the
Statistics Ministry does not permit judgements about the state of
the economy," he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
