<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All-Cypriot Parties Say Yes to Inter-community </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Political party leaders from both
Greek and Turkish communities in Cyprus met today and decided to
facilitate direct contact between community leaders to assist a
solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held at the Ledra Palace Hotel in the United
Nations-controlled buffer zone, and was attended by all Greek and
Turkish Cypriot parties except the major Turkish Cypriot National
Unity Party.
</P>
<P>
Gustave Feissel, U.N. Secretary-General's deputy special
representative for Cyprus, also attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement, read out by Feissel after the meeting, said
that the parties voiced support to the U.N. efforts to facilitate
"the urgent convening of direct negotiations between the two
communities on an overall settlement of the Cyprus problem."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, political party leaders themselves agreed to make
"every effort" to help establish direct contacts and telephone
communications between leaders of the two communities, the
statement asserted.
</P>
<P>
It added that they also agreed to co-sponsor in mid-1997 a
bicommunal concert by renowned Greek and Turkish composers, Mikis
Theodorakis and Zulgi Livaneli.
</P>
<P>
Feissel described such meetings as "absolutely helpful in the
U.N. efforts for a settlement" and said the parties, which
represent the totality of the island, have a very important role
to play in bringing about an overall settlement on Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
What is important, the U.N. envoy noted, is that "they (the
parties) are determined to overcome their differences and
facilitate the work" of the two communities' leaders who have to
negotiate the settlement.
</P>
<P>
Feissel called for more regular meetings of this kind and said
they are "a step in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took control of the northern third of the island in
the wake of short-lived coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
