<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Shocked over Renault's Handling of Restructuring Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac said
today that he was "shocked" by the method used by French automaker
Renault to announce its plans to close a plant in Belgium with the
loss of 3,100 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The closure of an assembly plant in Vilvoorde, Belgium, was
announced last Thursday by Renault secretary general Michel Davy
de Virville, as part of restructuring plans which, according to
union reports yesterday, will also lay off 2,764 workers in France
this year.
</P>
<P>
Renault announced the drastic restructuring plan after
registering a five billion franc (one billion U.S. dollar) loss in
1996 which it blamed on the globalization of the auto market and
fierce competition from other European automakers.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Alain Juppe has summoned Renault chief
Louis Schweitzer to a meeting over the way the announcement
was made about the closure of Vilvoorde plant, in which the French
state has a 46 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
Juppe, speaking ahead of the meeting later today, said that
the way Renault made its announcement "was not the right one,"
said French government spokesman Alain Lamassoure.
</P>
<P>
"I want to open a period of discussion and dialogue, and a
search for alternative solutions in respect of the procedures and
rules of the (European) Community and in Belgium and France," said
Juppe.
</P>
<P>
He said that while taking into account the "industrial logic"
and the "constraints of international competition," Renault should
also keep in mind the "human dimension" when carrying out its
restructuring plans.
</P>
<P>
"Renault should remain a great international enterprise... But
at the same time, one should not neglect the human dimension. The
method adopted (by Renault) is no good," said Juppe.
</P>
<P>
Juppe said he is also in touch with his Belgian counterpart
Jean-Luc Dehaene over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Karel van Miert, the EU commissioner for competition, said
Renault had failed to notify unions of its plans as laid down in EU
directives.
</P>
<P>
He said Renault did not take into account community directives
in deciding to close the Belgian factory.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the French union Force Ouvriere (FO) today called on
Renault to re-examine its production plans, shorten its working
week, adopt early retirement and employ more young workers.
</P>
<P>
"The case of Renault is not isolated. All the automobile
constructors in Europe have the same difficulties," said FO in a
communique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
