<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commission Asks Council to Approve ITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission(EC) today
approved the terms of the Information Technology Agreement (ITA)
which were agreed during the negotiations in Geneva over the
weekend and presented it for adoption to EU Council of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
The outline of an ITA deal was agreed among WTO countries at
their Ministerial meeting in Singapore last December, but they
left several issues outstanding.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, they decided to continue working until countries
representing 90 percent of the world IT trade were on board. This
target has now been exceeded with the decision by Malaysia,
Thailand, India, Romania, Estonia and Macao to present their
offers this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Declaration provides for IT tariffs to be
eliminated in four steps by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the EU and the U.S. decided to negotiate between
themselves a balanced additional acceleration of tariff cuts in
semi-conductors and other areas.
</P>
<P>
This, too, has been achieved: the EU will cut semi-conductor
tariffs in three stages by 1999, and the US will eliminate tariffs
on 2.6 billion US dollars worth of EU exports in July this year.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the EU semi-conductor industry will become a full
participant in the agreement reached between US and Japan
semi-conductor companies.
</P>
<P>
If the draft agreement is adopted by EU ministers, it will
enable the EU to commit itself definitively by the end-of-March
deadline fixed at Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elsie Leung on HK Future Legal System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Elsie Leung, Secretary of Justice
of the first government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR), said in Beijing today that it is her firm belief
that Hong Kong would be able to maintain its existing systems and
legal spirit, and safeguard human rights and independence of
justice.
</P>
<P>
Leung made this remark at a meeting of legislators from south
China's Guangdong Province, who are here attending the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), China's
legislature.
</P>
<P>
"To ensure the success of 'one country, two systems' in Hong
Kong, we will maintain its existing legal system," she said,
adding that her duty is to help the HKSAR government manage Hong
Kong according to law, maintain its existing legal system, and
ensure that the essence of the common laws, especially the spirit
of equality before the law and the rule of law, be preserved and
developed.
</P>
<P>
She claimed that she had been greatly honored to be appointed
Secretary of Justice of the first HKSAR government, and defined
her role as a legal advisor to the chief executive and other
government departments.
</P>
<P>
"All my colleagues in the Department of Justice are highly
professional and dedicated to their duties, and I believe that
with their cooperation, the establishment and operation of the
legal system in the HKSAR will proceed smoothly," she noted.
</P>
<P>
She vowed to safeguard the Basic Law of the HKSAR and the
common laws, and dauntlessly perform her duty with conscience
and impartiality.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Basic Law, she said, the NPC has given
the HKSAR the power of legislation, justice independence, and the
power of final adjudication, while only six national laws will be
applied in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the central government has granted the SAR great
legal independence, as long as the Basic Law is not contravened,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
She finally said that the NPC decision to retain most of Hong
Kong's existing laws has not only maintained Hong Kong's current
systems and policies, but also ensured the region's status in
international trade, for foreign businessmen can continue to
invest under a legal system they are quite familiar with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
