<HEADLINE> Ranariddh Expects Remaining Khmer Rouge to Join Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's First Prime Minister
Norodom Ranariddh said here today that he expects the remaining
Khmer Rouge will join the government soon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the headquarters of the Funcinpec, one
of the ruling parties in Cambodia's coalition cabinet, Ranariddh
said that the remaining Khmer Rouge in Anlong Veng may join the
government in the coming few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh said "Let the Khmer Rouge come back into the national
society under the umbrella of the King (Norodom Sihanouk), who is
the head of state and father of the nation."
</P>
<P>
Asked about Ta Mok, Khmer Rouge's chief of staff, who is
reportedly conducting negotiations in Anlong Veng with a team of
the government officials, Ranariddh reiterated his support for
creating an international tribunal to try Khmer Rouge leaders for
their crimes.
</P>
<P>
A team of government negotiators has been in the Khmer Rouge
territory since February 14. Deputy Chief of Staff Niek Bun
Chhay said that the talks will be positive in the coming five
days.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh gave a positive comment to Khmer Rouge leader Khieu
Samphan's alleged support to the 14 clauses of the platform of the
National United Front (NUF), a recently-formed political alliance
that groups the Funcinpec Party, the faction of the split
Buddhist Liberal Democratic Party led by Son Sann, the Khmer
Nation Party and the Khmer Neutral Party. Ranariddh is the
president of the NUF.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Khmer Rouge sent their message to him
expressing their hope to join the national community and their
worry that Anlong Veng might become another Samlot, where the two
coalition partners, the Funcinpec and the Cambodian people's Party
engaged in contest to win over breakaway Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
The first prime minister also confirmed that he had a luncheon
with Second Prime Minister Hun Sen, saying "this is a show of our
will to maintain political stability in the country." 
</P>
</TEXT>
