<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Police Expected to Switch to New bullets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- New York police are expected to
switch to more lethal hollow-point bullets which appear to be
safer for the general public, the New York Times reported today
quoting an announcement of the Police Department.
</P>
<P>
A hollow-point bullet expands on contact with human flesh, so
it kills or incapacitates more often than a conventional bullet.
And unlike a full metal bullet, it does not pass through a body or
ricochet, endangering bystanders.
</P>
<P>
"The hollow-point ammunition is the law enforcement standard in
every major metropolitan area. It protects both the police and the
citizens and replaces the dangerous military full-jacketed
ammunition," the report quoted Police Commissioner Howard Safir as
saying.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, after a series of shootings in which bystanders were
hit by police bullets, the department commissioned a study, firing
off 100,000 rounds of four or five different kinds of bullets, and
chose the hollow-point as the most effective. The department has
already earmarked 500,000 U.S. dollars to buy 9 million of the
bullets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
