<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Investors Flock to Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of Asian
businesses are putting more money in Europe, hoping to get access
to advanced technology and skills, according to a report of the
Journal of Commerce today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment by the developing nations of Asia
jumped to an annual average of 864 million U.S. dollars in the
1995-96 period from 100 million U.S. dollars in 1989-91.
</P>
<P>
Asian investments were mainly in the European Union, which is
the world's single-largest market for goods and services and the
globe's largest recipient of foreign direct investment.
</P>
<P>
The top deal in the last three years was the 347 million
purchase of Britain's Copthorne Hotels Holdings Ltd. by Hong
Kong's CDI Hotels International Ltd. in 1995. The second-biggest
deal was Daewoo Motor Co.'s 340 million U.S. dollar acquisition of
a Polish truck manufacturer in the same year. Another company from
the Republic of Korea, Korean Petroleum Development Corp.,
followed with the third-biggest deal when it invested 324 million
U.S. dollars in Texaco Inc.-U.K. North Sea of Britain in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The attraction of Europe is the growth tied to Central and
Eastern Europe, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Asian companies also want access to Europe's advanced
technology and skills and the research and development programs of
its corporations, the report said. The top European destinations
for Asian company investments are Britain, Germany and the
Netherlands, with Central and Eastern European countries growing
in importance.
</P>
<P>
Asian investments have been in both manufacturing -- especially
in electronics -- and in services. Textiles and apparel, leather,
chemicals and toys are also popular sectors for Asian investors.
</P>
<P>
Among the Asian investors in Europe, Hong Kong was the leader
with a 340 million U.S. dollars annual average during 1992-94,
mostly in the Wholesale and retail trade.
</P>
<P>
The Republic of Korea and Taiwan are close behind. Korean
companies have shifted from trading activities to specific
manufacturing sectors, largely in electrical and electronic
products, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD Refuses to Intervene in Renault Decision to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) said today that it is powerless
to intervene in the plan by French automaker Renault to close its
assembly plant in Vilvoorde, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Belgium today decided to lodge a complaint against Renault with
OECD, which has a code on multinational cooperations opposing
abrupt closure of plant and mass layoffs without pre-warning.
</P>
<P>
OECD said that its code on multinational cooperations does not
have the power of law for punishing those who do not follow it.
</P>
<P>
Belgium accused Renault of failing to observe an OECD code
which says: "The enterprises which plan to bring to their
activities alterations that could have heavy consequences on
employment, especially in the case of closure, should inform it
reasonably beforehand to the representatives of workers and public
authorities."
</P>
<P>
But the code also accommodates that in certain "isolated"
cases, it can be hard for enterprises to inform in advance the
employees its decision to close a plant.
</P>
<P>
OECD said that it cannot directly intervene in the dispute
between Renault and the Belgian government, which it said should
be dealt with on the levels of governments, enterprises and unions
concerned.
</P>
<P>
It also said that it does not have the "mandate" to
"mediate" between the two sides of the dispute or "make
judgement on the behavior of this or that enterprise." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asthma Medicine Could Harm Eyes, Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The large doses of inhaled steroids
people take to control asthma can significantly raise their risk
of developing glaucoma, a Canadian study said today.
</P>
<P>
The study of 48,118 Canadian patients over the age of 65
reviewed prescription and treatment records for patients who
consulted ophthalmologists.
</P>
<P>
The study found that patients who used high doses of inhaled
steroids for three months or longer were 44 percent more likely to
have treatment for glaucoma or high pressure in their eyes than
people who did not use the steroids or used them in small doses.
</P>
<P>
A high dose is about 1,600 micrograms of inhaled steroids daily
(the equivalent of eight puffs from an inhaler), according to Dr.
Samy Suissa, the McGill University epidemiologist who headed the
two-year study.
</P>
<P>
However, there was no increased risk seen in patients who used
moderate amounts, below 800 micrograms a day, Dr. Suissa said.
</P>
<P>
The results of the study appear in today's Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, there has been a trend to increasing doses of
steroids. At least 10 percent of the patients studied were using
dosages of 1,600 or higher.
</P>
<P>
"The message we want to give is that people should not stop
using steroids...They are very effective. But those who use
steroids, they should have their eyes regularly examined," Dr.
Suissa was quoted as saying by the Globe and Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
If high levels of steroids are essential for treatment, there
are drugs that can control the pressure in the eye, Dr. Suissa
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
