<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Government Proposes to Create Foundation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss Federal Council
(government) and the Swiss National Bank (SNB) have proposed to
create a Swiss Foundation for Solidarity to be financed with a
portion of profits from revaluation of the SNB's gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the Swiss government today in
Bern, no precise data can yet be released on money available to
the foundation since this depends on profits from revaluation of
the SNB gold reserves as well as on the timing foreseen for the
plan. But foundation assets of about seven billion Swiss francs
(about five billion U.S. dollars) are envisioned.
</P>
<P>
The SNB's gold reserves on hand are estimated at 2,600 tons.
Their bookkeeping value amounts to 5000 francs (about 3500 U.S.
dollars) per kilogram while their market value is about 17,000
francs (about 12,140 U.S. dollars) per kilogram. As foreseen by
the Swiss Committees for Economic Affairs and Taxes, such a
correction in value would allow a release of 14 billion francs
(about 10 billion U.S. dollars) in total. The release of such a
sum is liable to change in case the price of gold collapses due to
a surplus flow of gold on the market.
</P>
<P>
In order to start the foundation, Articles 38 and 39 of the
federal constitution must be amended, the SNB law must be revised,
and the legal basis for a public-law foundation must be created,
according to the press release. The Federal Council and the SNB
will strive to see that the foundation commences activity in 1998
if Parliament and the people agree.
</P>
<P>
As its name suggests, the press release says, the foundation's
goal would focus upon people in need, victims of catastrophes in
Switzerland and abroad, victims of genocide, torture, and other
violations of human rights (including victims of the Nazi
Holocaust and needy descendents) as well as support of
institutions involved in preventing the crisis situations
described.
</P>
<P>
As for the special fund of 100 million francs (about 71 million
U.S. dollars) created last week, it is for swift aid only to
victims and their descendents of the Holocaust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
