<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Adult Education Meeting Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Some 50 delegates from the
Commonwealth Association for the Education and Training of Adults
(CAETA) today started a three-day meeting in Harare to discuss ways
of developing adult education and training in poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
The conference will seek ways of bridging the gap between the
rich and the poor through education and training for self
reliance and economic empowerment.
</P>
<P>
It will also deal with gender issues, health, agriculture,
worker's education, and access to various training methods such as
distance education and open learning.
</P>
<P>
Opening the meeting, Director and Resident Representative of
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organisation (UNESCO) Anderson Shankanga said about one billion
adults worldwide, two thirds of them women, are illiterate.
</P>
<P>
He said programs on the empowerment of women should give
priority to expanding educational opportunities for women and
eliminating prejudices and stereotypes that both limit their access
to adult education.
</P>
<P>
He added an international meeting on adult education would be held
in Hamburg, Germany, from July 14 to 18, this year to discuss the
plight of adult literacy.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Chancellor of University of Zimbabwe Graham Hill said due
to many budgetary constraints, economic hardships and poverty in
general, many Commonwealth countries were finding it hard to make
ends meet.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, ''It is through education and training of adults that
we are able to reduce the degree of poverty for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
CAETA is an independent professional association which brings
together both individuals and organisations within the Commonwealth
who are concerned with education and training of adults. enditem

