<HEADLINE> Southern Africa Urged to Create Free Trade Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The formation of a free trade area
will speed up the eventual creation of a common market in southern
Africa, experts said here today.
</P>
<P>
A professor of agricultural economics Glenn Magagula and economics
lecturer Vakashile Simelane from the University of Swaziland said in
a joint paper that the free trade protocol signed by member countries
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) last August was
a clear indication of the region's recognition of need to integrate
the region's economy and stimulate trade.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates at a three-day consultative conference on
developing strategies for food security in southern Africa, they said
the majority of SADC states had now recognised that a process towards
elimination of all barriers to intra-regional trade was in the
region's best interest.
</P>
<P>
The experts said the protocol provided a framework for reform
measures aimed at the liberalisation of intra-regional markets and
implementation of mechanism for a phased withdrawal of tariff and
non-tariff barriers on goods and services originating in member
countries. enditem

