<HEADLINE> Israel Launches Air Strike at Hezbollah Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes rocketed this
afternoon guerrilla bases of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party
of God, in south Lebanon. There were no reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli jet fighters, covered by another two planes,
carried out the raid around 4:00 p.m. (14:00 GMT) at Iglim
Al-Toffah, or Province of Apple, an area often used by
Hezbollah militants as a springboard for attacks on the
Israeli-occupied border strip in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in the area said that the Israeli warplanes
fired two air-to-surface missiles at Wadi Mugaisbeh, between the
towns of Kfarmalki, Barti and Baslya in the area, some 60
kilometers southeast of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
The air raid followed frequent reconnaissance flights of the
Israeli warplanes at a low altitude over the areas of Nabatiyeh
and Iglim Al-Toffah in the central sector of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
This is the second Israeli air strike at the same area since
this month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the radio station of the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army (SLA) militia reported this afternoon that a
position of the SLA in Jezzine, south Lebanon, was attacked by
the guerrillas, but no casualties were caused.
</P>
<P>
However, today's air raid did not go beyond a daily trade of
fire between the Israeli forces, the SLA and the resistance
guerrillas on the last active battlefront of the Arab-Israeli
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Israel has established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security
zone" stretching from the Lebanese-Israeli border northward, and
armed the 2,500-strong SLA to patrol the buffer zone. 
</P>
