<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Insists on Strict Adherence to Euro Criteria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- German government today stressed that
the convergence criteria for qualifying for the planned single
European currency, the Euro, must be "strictly" adhered to by the
European Union (EU) member states.
</P>
<P>
In a report released Wednesday by German Finance Minister Theo
Waigel on the progress of the European Monetary Union, Bonn
painted a generally positive picture of the efforts being made by
EU member states in order to qualify for the Euro, which is due to
be launch on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"With the exception of Greece all the member states are now
striving to fulfill the convergence criteria in the year 1997,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
States wanting to join the Euro club are required to meet five
criteria under the EU Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
One of the rules is that a member's inflation rate should not
exceed a 1.5 percent limit over the inflation average of the three
countries with the lowest inflation.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Germany, the Netherlands and Finland registered the
lowest inflation rates, averaging 1.1 percent. That means the
maximum inflation rate should be 2.6 percent. Ten of the 15 EU
members had achieved that goal, while Britain and Portugal, with
inflation rate at 3.0 percent, were slightly above it, according
to the Bonn report.
</P>
<P>
On the criterion for long-term interest rates -- two percent
above the average of the three states with the lowest rates, the
1996 maximum stood at 8.7 percent. Eleven EU members, the same 10
meeting the inflation rule plus Britain, met this requirement,
Bonn said.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU members' performance on the Maastricht
criterion on public finances was less good according to the
report. Only four countries, Denmark, Ireland, Luxembourg and the
Netherlands, met the rule limits a state's budget deficit at a
maximum three percent of its gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The EU-wide deficit-to-GDP ratio averaged 4.4 percent last
year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the Bonn report also described EU countries' efforts
to meet the rule on national debt as "generally speaking
unsatisfactory". Under that rule, a EU state is required to bring
its overall national debt to less than 60 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
The Bonn report comes about one year before the decision being
made over which EU member states can make the first wave to join
the Euro club. That decision will be based on complete economic
data of 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
