<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-05 19:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Officials React Angrily With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian officials today
reacted angrily with Israel's decision to close four Palestinian
offices in East Jerusalem, warning that this could kill the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police today served letters of warning to the four
offices, which Israel believed to be run by the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA). Israel has declared that it would take
necessary steps if the offices did not shut down automatically.
</P>
<P>
The orders of closure were issued Tuesday night by Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu. He said these offices had
violated the Oslo accords which barred Palestinian official
activities in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference today, PNA Minister of
Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini denied the offices were linked
to the PNA. He blasted Israel's move as violation of peace accords,
warning that if Israel continued doing so, the PNA would not be
able to continue the peace path.
</P>
<P>
"Anyhow, whatever the Palestinian National Authority will do
if Israel goes on with their policy, this peace process will
die," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PNA Secretary Ahmed Abdel Rahman echoed the
warning, saying Israel's decision to shut down these offices
would lead to violence and confrontation. "If closing these
civil offices, they will have Hamas and Jihad in Jerusalem," he
said, referring to the two militant Islamic organizations which
have been launching attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the issue of Jerusalem should be settled
at the final stage of peace negotiations. He also urged the
Israeli government to be "realistic" on the issue, because "this
is a Palestinian city."
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials continued defending the decision to close
the Palestinian offices. Moshe Fogel, director of government
press office, said that the offices were in violation of the
Oslo accords. "We expect the Palestinians to live up to their
commitments and not to introduce any institutions or Palestinian
offices in Jerusalem," he said.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu, brushed aside the threats of violence by the
Palestinian side. He said that Israel was "doing the right
thing" and would not be deterred by any kind of threats or
international pressure.
</P>
<P>
He added that Israel was demanding reciprocity from the
Palestinian side in order to proceed forward with the peace
process. "Before we proceed with our next step in the peace
process, we expect the Palestinians to do something they are
obligated to do, and among the things they are obligated to do
is closing these offices," he told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Fogel indicated that the Israeli government ordered closure of
the PNA offices because it would be impossible to carry out
further troop withdrawals in the West Bank in face of the strong
pressure from the rightist members within the coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet is to hold a special meeting Thursday to
decide the scope of the first stage of the three-phase troop
redeployments, which should be completed within this week under
the Hebron agreement signed in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
