<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Italy Sign Agreement on Return of Axum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Ministry
today announced that an agreement was signed between the
Ethiopian and Italian governments on the return of the Axum
obelisk, a historical relic, taken 60 years ago by the fascist
Italy under Benito Mussolini.
</P>
<P>
A statement quoted by the Ethiopian News Agency said, the
agreement was signed by Ethiopian Vice-foreign minister Tekeda
Alemu and his Italian counterpart Rino Seri.
</P>
<P>
A 13-member Ethiopian delegation led by the vice-minister has
attended the meeting convened in Rome by the joint committee set
up to facilitate the return of the Axum obelisk.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said a communique issued by the two parties has
stated that the obelisk now standing in Rome will be returned to
Ethiopia before the end of 1997 and the Italian government has
agreed to work to this end in line with the accord concluded.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the return of the historical relic, including
transportation and the choosing of the site for its erection will
be done in accordance to the agreement, the ministry added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry today also announced
that the Ethiopian government, upon the return of the obelisk to
its historical owner, will present a gift to the Italian
government as a token of the relationship between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Axum obelisks are most striking relics of ancient Axum kingdom
established about 2,000 years ago in Axum, an ancient city
located 600 kms north of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
They are made of single blocks of granite carved in the
representation of multi-storey buildings. The Italian aggressors
looted one of Axum obelisk in 1937. 
</P>
</TEXT>
