<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Battles are raging in the southern
Albanian town of Delvino between rioters and the army, while the
conflict is expected to spread to Sarande, according to a report
this afternoon from the Athens News Agency (ANA) correspondent in
Gjirokaster.
</P>
<P>
The wounded have been taken to hospital in Sarande and
eyewitnesses say there must have been casualties, although there
have been no deaths reported as yet.
</P>
<P>
Military reinforcements from Gjirokaster have been forced to
turn back as the roads to both Delvino and Sarande have been
blocked by demonstrators. Sarande has been surrounded and at any
moment the military is expected to move in against the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
A later ANA dispatch from Gjirokaster said that the operation
in Delvino began at 10:30 local time, when heavily armed troops
and plainclothes policemen moved into the town, saying that they
had no order to shoot.
</P>
<P>
When they saw armed civilians however, they reportedly opened
fire without warning, leading to a prolonged exchange of fire with
armed residents.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, reports said that oxygen bottles and other
medical supplies were being sent from Greek island of Corfu to
Sarande hospital. 
