Abdallah Kigoda said there have been internal and external
complaints from prospecting big and small scale miners caused by
bureaucratic practices by the Dodoma based offices which could
only be solved if the offices were transferred for close
supervision in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
He said bureaucracy, coupled with corrupt practices among
mineral officials had so far denied the nation the necessary
revenue apart from retarding development in the mineral sector.
</P>
<P>
Kigoda cautioned there is need to have deliberate efforts in
creating conducive environment to improve the mineral sector
against the present trend whereby Tanzania is a mineral
extracting field whose benefits are enjoyed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
He directed mineral officials in the country to start creating
ways of reducing license issuing red tape at district level.
</P>
<P>
The minister also warned against application of dynamite in
extracting minerals which he said had so far caused serious
environmental destruction apart from claiming human lives.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, sponsored by the World Bank, is being attended
by 90 delegates from six mineral zones in the country and
government departments. 
