<HEADLINE> Rinderpest Epidemic Spreading in East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- An epidemic of rinderpest is
currently sweeping across the Kenyan border into Tanzania with
potentially devastating consequences for the eastern and southern
Africa, a U.N. report said today.
</P>
<P>
The latest February report of "Food Supply Situation and Crop
Prospects in Sub-Saharan Africa" distributed by the U.N. Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) said that the epidemic has been
moving from endemic areas in northeastern Kenya and Somalia
across eastern and southern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The report warned that rinderpest would sweep through Tanzania
and on into southern Africa unless checked.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, last October an outbreak of a disease
with clinical signs of rinderpest was detected in the Nairobi
National Park.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the Kenyan government notified the FAO of the
new outbreak of rinderpest which was later detected in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
A survey indicated that the disease was affecting both cattle
and wildlife near the Nairobi National Park and the wildlife was
being affected more seriously.
</P>
<P>
In 1994/95, Kenya experienced an outbreak of rinderpest which
apparently affected only wildlife in the national parks of
southeast Kenya with a loss of about 50 percent of the buffalo
and 80 percent of the kudu populations in West Tsavo National
Park.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the Kenya News Agency reported that Kenya
and Tanzania had succeeded in controlling a rinderpest outbreak
hitting the border areas between Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
About 400,000 head of cattle have been vaccinated and the
epidemic has been under control owing to the cooperation between
the two neighboring countries, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
