<HEADLINE> Brittan Issues Stark Warning on British Eurosceptics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC)
Vice-President Sir Leon Brittan has warned Britain's ruling
Conservative Party that any attempt to play a Eurosceptic card in
the coming general election would be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Guardian newspaper, Brittan
said that an anti-European electoral stance would not only fail
to woo voters but eventually undermine Britain's position in the
crucial negotiations of the European Union's (EU)
Inter-Governmental Conference as well.
</P>
<P>
Brittan, a former British Conservative minister in the 1980s,
said: "Those who think they can make Euroscepticism into an
election issue by putting clear blue water between Conservatives
and Labor are making a big mistake."
</P>
<P>
"It is quite clear that (the Conservatives') any move towards
Euroscepticism will be pretty rapidly followed by the Labor Party.
As a consequence, whoever wins the election will have a difficult
hand to play in the Inter-Governmental Conference end-game," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Brittan, who is also EC's trade commissioner, argued that while
Europe had benefited from the British example, Britain had also
reaped significant benefits from its EU membership.
</P>
<P>
"Again and again we see the fact that countries the size and
weight of Britain play a minor part in negotiations, but because
of Britain's position in Europe it is able to play a major role
and has been successful in persuading the EU to take a liberal
line," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
