<HEADLINE> Swazi Strikers Return to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- About 15,000 Swazi
agriculutral and forestry workers returned to work today after a
month-long stayaway called by the Swaziland Federation of Trade
Unions (SFTU), informed sources reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide strike, which began on February 3, was intended
to force the Swazi government to meet 27 labor and political
demands, including the lifting of a 24-year-old ban on political
parties.
</P>
<P>
The indefinite strike suspended after four top SFTU leaders,
who had been on trial on charges of spearheading the national
stayaway, were acquitted on February 26.
</P>
<P>
However, the present situation in the tiny kingdom appeared to
be far from normalized between the government and the SFTU, with
a meeting between the two sides's negotiating teams being
postponed this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted unidentified Swazi
officials as saying that the postponement of the meeting might
have been caused by government anger at the SFTU's participation
in blockading Swaziland's borders on Monday this week.
</P>
<P>
Sales in major supermarkets in Swaziland have reportedly
dropped sharply due to protestors's blockade of goods coming in
and out of the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the SFTU, the Congress of South African Trade
Unions, which is in support of the SFTU, also reportedly took
part in the siege, blocking trucks from entering and leaving
Swaziland at two main border posts with South Africa. 
</P>
