<HEADLINE> Ghana Divests 182 State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 182 state-owned
enterprises were divested in Ghana by the end of 1996, including
18 joint ventures with foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today quoted Siegfried Sedziefa, public
relations manager of the Divestiture Implementation Committee, as
saying that the country's divestiture program is an ambitious
attempt to inject private capital and technology into the
economy.
</P>
<P>
It is also to reduce the size of public sector and improve the
performance of state-owned enterprises by mobilizing private
sector management, Sedziefa said on Monday in Accra, capital of
Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian and foreign firms not on the register were invited to
participate in the program, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Sedziefa, such firms are to submit the full names
of their firms, addresses and contact details, date of
establishment, and list of directors and shareholders or
partners.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to submit the names and addresses of bankers
and auditors, and a statement of their firms' capabilities, he
added. 
</P>
