<HEADLINE> Meeting on Korea Peace Proposals Begins in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), the Republic of
Korea and the United States started their meetings here today to
discuss proposals for the proposed four-way talks aimed at a peace
treaty formally ending the war on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
"The atmosphere was pleasant, they were all very pleasant with
another," New York Foreign Press Center spokesman Kenneth Bailes
told reporters. Bailes observed the start of the meeting in a
conference room in Manhattan's Hilton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
Although Wednesday's schedule was reportedly modest, the
meeting itself was significant because it was reportedly the first
time in more than 20 years for the officials from Pyongyang and
Seoul to have sat in the same room to talk peace.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses told reporters that the meeting began with members of
the three delegations shaking hands, exchanging small talks and
pleasantries.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, described by the U.S. State Department as a "joint
briefing," stemmed from last April's proposal to DPRK by U.S.
President Bill Clinton and South Korean President Kim Young-Sam
for four-way talks including China to work out a peace agreement
to replace the armistice that ended the 1950-53 war on the Korean
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
A witness told reporters that South Korean delegation head,
deputy minister for political affairs Song Young Shik told his
DPRK counterpart Kim Gye Gwan that Wendesday's meeting "is a
significant event." Kim is vice minister for forein affairs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation is headed by Deputy Assistant Secretary of
State for East Asian and Pacific Affairs Charles Kartman.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that the New York meeting was convened at
the request of Pyongyang, which wanted more information on
Washington and Seoul's proposals for the four-way talks.
</P>
<P>
But the actual negotiations are not expected to start until
July or so, a senior American official said earlier in the week.


nnnn
03:51 03:51 g # NAB
