<HEADLINE> Ghana's Currency Depreciates Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ghanaian currency shed 33 Cedis
in one week, opening Monday at an average rate of 1,820 to one
U.S. Dollar from 1,787 last week, the Ghana News Agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted currency dealers in Accra, the Ghanaian
capital, as attributing the depreciation of the local currency to
high demand for hard currency to pay for imports, amidst low
export earnings.
</P>
<P>
The Cedi exchanged at 12 to one Dollar ten years ago, after
the country decided to fully liberalize the economy, now
considered by multilateral finance institutions as one of the
most vibrant on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a report reaching here today, the CFA
Franc, which is the legal tender in 13 French-speaking African
countries, also dropped considerably, averaging 575 to one Dollar
from the nominal rate of 565.7, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Dakar, Senegal, on Tuesday, the currency exchanged at 560
(buying) and 590 (selling) to one Dollar, compared with 551 and
581, respectively, last week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
