<HEADLINE> Canada Seeks WTO Panel on Australian Salmon Imports Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada will ask the World Trade
Organization (WTO) for a dispute settlement panel on Australia's
ban on imports of uncooked salmon, the Canadian government said
today.
</P>
<P>
The request for a dispute settlement panel will be made
formally to the WTO's Dispute Settlement Body on March 20, the
government announced in a statement.
</P>
<P>
In 1975, Australia introduced a new quarantine measure that
prohibited the import of uncooked salmon products, which requires
imported salmon to be either heat treated or canned.
</P>
<P>
Because of this, Canadian exports of fresh, frozen or chilled
salmon were virtually banned from the Australian market.
</P>
<P>
To resolve the dispute, Canada held a number of technical
discussions with Australia, but little agreement was reached.
</P>
<P>
In October 1995, Canada requested WTO consultations with
Australia to settle the problem. The consultations were held in
the following month, without reaching a resolution.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, Australia announced that it would
maintain its current ban on uncooked salmon products.
</P>
<P>
"Canada's position is that the ban cannot be supported on
scientific grounds and is inconsistent with Australia's
obligations under the WTO," Canadian International Trade Minister
Art Eggleton said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Canadian salmon producers in British Columbia have been
unfairly denied access to Australia's market for over 20 years,"
Oceans Minister Fred Mifflin said, adding that he "strongly
supports" the decision to request a WTO panel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
