<HEADLINE> Renault President Agrees to Consult Belgians on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- President of the French automaker
Renault Louis Schweitzer said this afternoon that he will consult
"without delay" with the staff of Renault's Vilvoorde plant in
Belgium over his plan to close the plant, which will result in a
layoff of 3,100 workers.
</P>
<P>
Following a one-hour meeting with French Prime Minister Alain
Juppe, Schweitzer said that the consultations will focus on
measures of compensation or even redeployment of the plant.
</P>
<P>
He said that Renault will be committed to all the rules of the
European Union, France and Belgium over plant closure and mass
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Alain Juppe
expressed their displeasure over the way Renault decided to close
the Vilvoorde plant, as well as its plan to lay off 2,764 workers
in France this year.
</P>
<P>
Renault's plan triggered angry protests from Belgium and
criticism from the European Union, and has met with strong
opposition from both rightwing and leftwing parties in the French
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Nine hundred Belgian workers from the Vilvoorde plant today
marched to a Renault plant in Douai, northern France, to protest
the plan.
</P>
<P>
Juppe said in a communique this afternoon that he has asked
Schweitzer to "engage without delay in all the useful
consultations within the framework of the Belgian law and European
legislation" with "all the negotiating partners concerned, the
staff of the enterprise, and the local and national authorities of
Belgium."
</P>
<P>
He said that he has also informed his Belgian counterpart,
Jean-Luc Dehaene, about the contents of his meeting with
Schweitzer and the promises the latter has made.
</P>
<P>
He also asked Renault to hold dialogue with the representatives
of its staff on its plan to lay off 2,764 French workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
