<HEADLINE> More Canadians to Die from Cancer This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- An estimated 130,800 cases of
cancer will be diagnosed in Canadians this year, and some 60,700
Canadians will die from the disease, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
This year's level of cancer cases is expected to be 36 percent
higher than that of 1987, and the number of deaths about 25
percent higher.
</P>
<P>
"The total number of new cases and deaths for all cancers has
risen largely as a result of a growing and aging population," the
federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 71 percent of new cases and 80 percent of
deaths this year will occur among those who are at least 60 years
old.
</P>
<P>
Lung cancer will kill more Canadians than any other form of
cancer in 1997, 10,600 men and 6,300 women.
</P>
<P>
Prostate cancer will again be the most commonly diagnosed
cancer among men, with an anticipated 19,800 cases, which is more
than double the level a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The most frequent diagnosis among women will be breast cancer,
with an estimated 18,400 new cases, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
