<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Reaffirms Opposition to NATO's Eastward Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today reaffirmed Russia's opposition to NATO's eastward expansion
plans in his annual message to the Federal Assembly (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he believed the enlargement of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization is against Russia's interests and is fraught
with dangers which could create a new split of Europe, Itar-Tass
news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The presidential message says that without Russia, Europe has
never been and will never be able to create an effective security
structure.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin called for firm mutual security guarantees, including
nuclear ones, a reliable mechanism for consultation and
decision-making with NATO.
</P>
<P>
The president insisted that these arrangements should be based
on a clear-cut legal framework.
</P>
<P>
He said it was time to adapt the Treaty on Conventional Armed
Forces in Europe to the new political realities on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was signed in November 1990 between the 16 NATO
member states and the six member states of the then Warsaw Pact.
Russia has been calling for the terms of the treaty, particularly
on weapons deployment, to be updated to take account of the
geopolitical changes in Europe since the collapse of the Soviet
Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In his message, Yeltsin also said that he would exert every
effort to reach agreement on equitable and long-lasting
cooperation with the West at his summit with U.S. President Bill
Clinton in the Finnish capital of Helsinki on March 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
