<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Government Fails to Win Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's three-party government
today narrowly lost a confidence motion in the lower house of
parliament due to some ruling MPs' absence from the house voting.
</P>
<P>
The motion, tabled by Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba seeking
a confidence vote for his coalition government, was defeated in
the 205-seat house as 101 MPs voted for and 92 against with others
abstaining from the voting held in the evening.
</P>
<P>
Such a motion required a majority of at least 103 votes in the
lower house to pass under the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
The government, which came to power in September 1995, was
reduced to a minority last December by a no-confidence motion
sponsored by the main opposition party, the Communist Party of
Nepal (United Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML).
</P>
<P>
Some MPs of the ruling side were absent from today's house
session or abstained from voting, resulting in the defeat of the
confidence motion, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Deuba, who has been leading the coalition government formed by
his National Congress party, the National Democratic Party and the
Nepal Goodwill Party since September 1995, sought the vote of
confidence in the house under pressure from the opposition after
his government lost majority support in the house over two months
ago.
</P>
<P>
Deuba's government survived a no-confidence motion sponsored by
the CPN-UML last December by securing only 84 votes against the
opposition motion in the 205-seat house.
</P>
<P>
It is expected the Deuba government would resign in the next
few days and the CPN-UML is likely to form an alternative
government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
