<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Optimistic on China's Accession to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) hopes the
terms of China's accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO)
can be agreed by the end of the year, Vice-President of the EU
Commission Leon Brittan said today.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union firmly believes that membership of the WTO
on the right terms will be good for China and good for the world
trading system," Brittan said in a statement at the resumption of
formal negotiations on China's WTO membership in Geneva today.
</P>
<P>
The EU is determined to ensure that the issue remains at the
top of the WTO agenda throughout this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Government responded positively to my request in
Beijing last November that the talks should be relaunched in
earnest," he said.
</P>
<P>
In January, the EU sent a large, high-level delegation to China
for exploratory talks on China's WTO membership. "This indicates
the importance we attach to the issue," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Brittan pointed out that although major obstacles of substance
still remain, the talks were conducted in a "positive atmosphere."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, the time has come to turn the new mood of
optimism into concrete progress on the ground.
</P>
<P>
The EU believes that if all sides muster sufficient political
will, the terms of China's accession could be agreed by the end of
the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged China to make "bold and meaningful commitments" to its
market reform, noting that the EU believes the negotiations must
focus on trading rights, services and tariff and non-tariff
measures.
</P>
<P>
"Our distinctive approach is that if Beijing respects certain
basic obligations at the outset, fixed transition periods should
be agreed for China's acceptance of the remaining WTO
commitments," he said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
He added this approach recognizes China's special position as a
country that is still in transition from a planned economy to a
market economy.
</P>
<P>
China submitted its request for the restoration of its
membership of GATT (General Agreement of Tariffs and Trade) in
1986 and has since been engaged in relevant negotiations with GATT
and its successor the WTO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
