<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Soars in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus, the
broadest measure of trade in goods and services, rose sharply in
January, reversing the year-on-year downward trend of the last 17
months, the government said today.
</P>
<P>
Data released on Thursday by the Finance Ministry showed the
current account surplus surged 362 percent over January 1996, up
from 32.5 billion yen (266 million U.S. dollars) to 150.7 billion
yen (1.25 billion dollars), the first year-on-year rise since
August 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the surplus was down 23.1 percent on December's 820.7
billion yen.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the strong increase to a 26 percent rise
in overseas direct investment and net income from Japanese
investment in overseas securities to 518.8 billion yen (4.29
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Also contributing to the rise was the shrinking of the deficit
in services which fell 12 percent from 581.2 billion yen (4.81
billion dollars) in January 1996 to 513.7 billion yen (4.25
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The merchandise trade surplus, however, fell 15.5 percent to
229.3 billion yen (1.9 billion dollars), extending its
year-on-year decline to 26 consecutive months.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew 17.3 percent to 3471.8 billion yen (28.9 billion
dollars) but imports jumped 20.6 percent to 3242.5 billion yen (27
billion dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts Call for Better Wild Bird Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE (Hebei), March 6 (Xinhua) -- The China Wildlife
Protection Association and a group of local and foreign experts
today urged society to develop habits of loving birds and nature,
asking people to pay attention to wild birds during the spring, to
learn more about them and to improve their conditions.
</P>
<P>
Chen Runsheng, the association's executive secretary general,
told Xinhua that wild birds have mostly been destroyed by people
killing and trafficking in them and that some species are on the
brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
This morning, the experts, more than 100 in all, visited
Beidaihe, a scenic coastal city in north China's Hebei Province,
to have a look at a local nature reserve for birds.
</P>
<P>
Calling birds friends of human beings, the experts asked people
not to try to capture, buy, or eat wild birds and to let them live
and reproduce in nature.
</P>
<P>
All of society, especially young people, should develop an
interest in them and a habit of seeing birds as a natural part of
wildlife, they said.
</P>
<P>
"We advocate a new style of bird-watching: leaving nothing but
footprints and taking away nothing but photos," Chen Runsheng said.
</P>
<P>
The China Wildlife Protection Association was set up in 1983
and now has more than 30,000 members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
