<HEADLINE> China to Take Stake in Hong Kong Banknote Printer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China Banknote Printing and
Minting Corporation (CBPMC) will purchase a small stake in Hong
Kong's banknote printer.
</P>
<P>
An agreement on the deal has been signed between the CBPMC, a
subsidiary of China's central bank, the People's Bank of China
(POBC), and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), which
exercises the functions of a central bank in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese banknote printer will pay 42.5 million HK dollars (
5.5 million U.S. dollars) for 3.82 million shares, or a
15-percent stake, in Hong Kong Note Printing (HKNP), which is
wholly owned by the Hong Kong government.
</P>
<P>
HKNP prints banknotes issued by the three note-issuing banks in
Hong Kong -- the Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation,
Standard Charter Bank and the Bank of China. The Hong Kong
government bought the HKNP plant from the British note printer De
La Rue in April 1996, putting an end to a 100-year practice of
entrusting note printing to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Donald Tsang, financial secretary of the Hong Kong government,
said HKNP would benefit from the new business relationship with
the CBPMC, which has expertise in banknote printing, including
designing, plate-making and printing of banknotes.
</P>
<P>
The CBPMC operates 15 printing and minting plants and a
technology development institute in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
