<HEADLINE> Indo-Pakistan Dialogue to Resume on March 28: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indo-Pakistan foreign
secretary level talks, stalled for the last three years, are
likely to be resumed here on March 28, Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by outgoing Pakistan High Commissioner to
India Riaz Khokhar, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmed will arrive here on
March 28 for three days to hold bilateral talks with his Indian
counterpart Salman Haider, Khokhar told an Indian newspaper before
leaving for his new assignment as Islamabad's envoy to Washington,
PTI said.
</P>
<P>
The last round of foreign secretary-level talks between the two
countries was held in January 1994 in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Khokhar told the newspaper that Pakistan Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan might send a reply to his India counterpart I.K.
Gujral's letter either today or tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Gujral had sent the letter last week congratulating Gohar on
his appointment as foreign minister of Pakistan and reiterating
the H.D. Deve Gowda government's readiness to resume a dialogue at
an appropriate level and on all issues of mutual concerns.
</P>
<P>
Khokhar said that since Kashmir was the "core issue" between
the two countries, Islamabad would try to seek an "amicable
solution to it first."
</P>
<P>
"Kashmir is a fundamental issue for Pakistan and all other
matters are a consequence of it. How can you touch peripheral
issues and leave the fundamental problem unattended?" he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Kashmir issue could be put in cold storage to try
other issues including ways to boost trade, Khokhar is reported to
have said, "the other issues do not create tension. We want to
address the main issue first which creates tension and affects the
people of the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"We can also talk on trade and other such issues but there is
no question of putting Kashmir in cold storage even for a moment,"
PTI quoted him as saying.  
</P>
</TEXT>
