<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Foreign Debt Breaks 200 Billion Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia's foreign debt, for the
first time, broke the 200 billion Australian dollars barrier in
December 1996 quarter, the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS)
said today.
</P>
<P>
In its latest international investment survey, the ABS said the
net foreign debt rose to 202.367 billion Australian dollars
(158.85 billion US dollars) from an upwards revised 196.042
billion Australian dollars (153.89 billion US dollars) in the
September quarter.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of net debt to gross domestic product was 40.3
percent, the highest level in three years, while in the September
quarter it was 39.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Opposition treasury spokesman Gareth Evans said in a statement
that in the first nine months since its coming into office, the
government had added 16 billion Australian dollars (12.56 billion
US dollars) to foreign debt, compared with 18 billion Australian
dollars (14 billion US dollars) in the last two years of the
previous government.
</P>
<P>
Australian Democrats leader Cheryl Kernot blamed an increase in
foreign takeovers of Australian assets under the current
government for the resurgence in debt levels, "Australia cannot
afford to keep losing so much of our national income without
compromising our economic independence."
</P>
<P>
Economists called on the government to fulfill its intention to
cut spending in the May budget, and warned the debt ratio could
blow out even further as the economy gained strength this year and
pushed out the current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank senior economist John Peters said "the latest
snapshot of Australia's external debt position is a timely
reminder in the lead up to the May budget of just why the
government needs to continue to tighten the fiscal screws and
promote a higher level of savings."
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank economist Tim Moloney said "today's figures
should serve to sharpen the Treasurer's resolve to keep the
government's balanced budget objective on track."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
