<HEADLINE> Traditional Medication to Be Allowed in Malaysia's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Health Minister
Chua Jui Meng said today Malaysia's Medical Act 1971 will be
amended to allow for the practice of traditional medicines in
hospitals in the country.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after a social function here that the draft
on the proposed amendment is in its final stage and is expected to
be tabled during the mid-year Parliament sitting.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry had already formed a committee to ensure
the types of traditional medicines to be used.
</P>
<P>
At present, Malaysia's Medical Act contained provisions which
did not allow for traditional treatment to be applied in
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Modern and traditional methods of treatment should be combined
to produce a more complete system of treatment, the minister said,
adding not all western medicines were effective and not all
traditional medication were bad.
</P>
<P>
He said the combination of both methods of treatment was being
practiced successfully in several countries such as South Korea,
Japan and Australia.  
