<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indonesian Forests Vital to Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jakarta, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
recently again called on its people to pay serious attention to
the protection of its tropical forests which occupies a decisive
position in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 12 million of Indonesia's 200 million people rely on
tropical forests for a living, Toehadi, head of the Forestry
Ministry's counseling service, said at a meeting on forests
Wednesday in Mataram, West Nusatenggara Province.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's total forests covering 144 million hectares, or
about 74.6 percent of its 193 million hectares of land, were
recently declared the earth's biggest and remaining functional
"lung" (apart from that in the Amazon of Brazil).
</P>
<P>
The country has been utilizing its forest resources on a full
scale in the past 20 years, beginning with the export of logs,
which in fiscal year 1978/79 earned the country a 41-percent share
of the world market for roundwood.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the forestry sector has become the country's third
most important source of foreign exchange, following oil and gas
and textiles.
</P>
<P>
The important role of forestry in the Indonesian economy has
prompted the government to strive for sustainable forest
management.
</P>
<P>
The move is considered timely since the country's forest area
has begun to decline due to the conversion of natural forests into
 agricultural land and resettlement areas, forest fires and
nomadic farming.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the Forestry Ministry Kardjono Kadarsin said
earlier that the country's deforestation has taken a toll on about
1.3 million hectares per year.
</P>
<P>
In face of such a situation, the Indonesian government has
introduced many regulations, including cooperation with foreign
agencies, in a bid to maintain its natural forests.
</P>
<P>
Big strides were made in the 1970s when Indonesia analyzed and
divided its 144 million hectares of forests into four categories:
protected forests, conservation forests, conversion forests and
production forests.
</P>
<P>
The division aimed to ensure the survival of fauna and flora
for the benefit of future generations, to allow the country to use
its forests for employment and economic growth and to plan for the
economic activities and population growth of cities.
</P>
<P>
To enable the country to use its forests for employment and
economic growth, the government has begun developing more than 3
million hectares of timber estates and it plans to open 3.5
million hectares more soon, Forestry Minister Djamaloedin
Soeryohadikoesoemo said recently.
</P>
<P>
The government has also introduced the Indonesian Selective
Logging System, under which forest concessionaires are required to
ensure the sustainable exploitation of forest resources.
</P>
<P>
The policies and measures have reduced the volume of tree
felling from 38 million cubic meters in 1989/90 to 25 million
cubic meters in 1993/94, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Illustrating the importance of forests to the country's
economy, Soeryohadikoesoemo said about 2.5 million people are
working in the wood industry while 1.2 million others are employed
in support industries and businesses indirectly related to the
forestry industry.
</P>
<P>
Data from the Forestry Ministry indicate that Indonesia's
forest-based industries have contributed 15 percent to the
country's total exports, making them the third largest foreign
exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's forestry policy in the Sixth Five-Year Development
Plan (1994-1999) stresses increased public participation in forest
development and conservation for the sake of the country's
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
