<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Going All Out to Build Farmland Irrigation Works (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China produced 48 billion kg of
grain in 1996, a year with serious flooding affecting many parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Deputies to the on-going session of China's legislature,
National People's Congress (NPC), attributed the good harvest to
nationwide efforts to build farmland irrigation works.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Dengquan, a NPC deputy and vice-minister of water
conservancy, said some 20 million ha of arable land has been
flooded over the past three years, causing economic losses up to
220 billion yuan. However, China has set three records in grain
production from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite a marked improvement in water conservancy projects, the
Chinese government was unsatisfied with China's present irrigation
conditions, in which floods and dry spells still loom over a large
area in its endeavor to feed the world's biggest population.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report at the Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress, Premier Li Peng promised that
China decides to establish a special fund and increase its input
in agricultural production. And, according to the funding system,
the central government will be responsible for harnessing big
rivers while local governments will be in charge of smaller rivers
and lakes.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Li urged local farmers to carry out farmland
improvement and water conservancy projects as well as improvement
of small drainage areas to minimize possible losses to be brought
by natural adversities.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu Dengquan, the vice minister, China's farmland
acreage brought under irrigation is increasing at a rate of
330,000 ha annually at a time when crop acreage is decreasing by
the same amount amid rapid urban and highway construction, and
thriving township industry.
</P>
<P>
Since last winter, he said, Some 100 million farmers have been
working at worksites of irrigation projects throughout China,
pouring in a total investment of 27.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
In Sichuan, China's most populous and a major agriculture
province, some 15 million people thrown in a total of one billion
work days during the latest winter-spring period on water
conservancy projects with 1.6 billion yuan in investment, a marked
increase over the previous years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Going All Out to Build Irrigation Works (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
International financial organizations have also granted the
province 94 million US dollars in loans to help build two major
water conservancy projects in Sichuan. In addition, the provincial
government has spared 40 million yuan from its tight budget in
such construction.
</P>
<P>
Apart from government funds, local farmers have also been
encouraged to raise funds in the construction of irrigation
ditches, canals and other water conservancy projects. Some elderly
farmers even sold their ready-made coffins and the kids spared
their changes, described by Dai Xianlu, a farmer deputy from
Sichuan's Renshou County.
</P>
<P>
Hubei, which experienced serious flooding last year, reaped a
record high grain harvest in 1996 despite torrential rains that
caused 31.1 billion yuan in economic losses, the highest in
history.
</P>
<P>
Jia Zhijie, provincial party secretary, also attributed the
good harvest to years of efforts in water conservancy
construction. Jia said as a leading grain producer, Hubei will
allocate two billion yuan annually over the next five years in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
In the northwest China, which is frequented by dry spells,
Shaanxi, Gansu and Qinghai provinces and autonomous regions of
Ningxia and Xinjiang have joined hands and built 2,057 major
reservoirs with a total storage capacity of 14.12 billion square
meters to quench the thirst of crops.
</P>
<P>
The whole country is seething with enthusiasm to build
irrigation project and water conservancy items, which has find
expressions nationwide, either in east China's Anhui Province
where major floods or waterlogging claimed a heavy loss of lives
and economic damages in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In the Yangtze River, Yellow River, Haihe River and Huaihe
River valleys, the four major river drainage areas, a large number
of emergency facilities such as buildings, bridges and highways
are being built.
</P>
<P>
The largest of these projects is the gigantic Three Gorges
Hydroelectric Project which is built to prevent turbulent water
flood from surging downstream Yangtze River and the Liaolangdi
Hydroelectric Project on the Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
The river interception of these two projects due late this year
will signify a new historic period for building water conservancy
projects in China, experts say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
