<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Welcomes Malaysia's Entry Into IORI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 6 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela tonight welcomed Malaysia's entry into the Indian
Ocean Rim Initiative (IORI), saying, "We look forward to further
joint actions in this forum."
</P>
<P>
Both South Africa and Malaysia carry the same conviction
through into the wider world, by promoting the role and
aspirations of the developing world in various forums such as the
BAH365AAA095S06PEQL21:3221:322099
Non-Aligned Movement and the Commonwealth of Nations, Mandela said
at a state banquet hosted in his honor by Malaysian Supreme Head
of State Tuanku Ja'afar here.
</P>
<P>
The IORI, initiated two years ago, is now known as the Indian
Ocean Rim Association for Regional Cooperation (IOR-ARC) whose
first ministerial meeting is being held in Mauritius. It groups 14
countries bordering the Indian Ocean -- Australia, India,
Indonesia, Kenya, Madagascar, Malaysia, Mauritius, Mozambique,
Oman, Singapore, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Tanzania and Yemen.
</P>
<P>
The main objectives of the IOR-ARC are to promote a sustained
growth and development of the region and member states and to
formulate and implement projects for economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Praising Malaysia for being among the leading countries in the
global struggle against apartheid, Mandela, who arrived here
earlier today for a five-day visit, said Malaysia has "rich
experience" in uniting a diverse society on the basis of equity
and social advancement which is another common factor between the
two nations.
</P>
<P>
On economic cooperation, Mandela said that within three years,
bilateral trade has more than doubled and Malaysia is now the
fourth largest investor in South Africa, overtaking many
long-established countries in the process.
</P>
<P>
Mandela also congratulated Malaysia on its election as the
president of the 51st session of the U.N. General Assembly,
describing it as a certain indication that Malaysia is willing and
ready to assume greater responsibility in global matters.
</P>
<P>
He said his mission here is to reaffirm and strengthen the
historical ties that bind the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
