<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Senate Approves Reconciliation Accord With Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Czech Senate today approved a
joint declaration of reconciliation between the Czech Republic and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was signed on January 21 by Czech Prime
Minister Vaclav Klaus and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl and was
aimed at burying the difficulties left over from World War II.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, Germany admitted its historical
responsibility for the World War II, expressed its sorrow for the
1938-45 Nazi occupation of Czech lands and asked the Czech people
for "forgiveness."
</P>
<P>
Prague also stated its regret for expelling 2.5 million Sudeten
Germans from Czechoslovakia in 1945 and confiscating their
property.
</P>
<P>
The accord, drawn up after two years' delicate talks, also
included Germany's support for the Czech Republic's efforts to
obtain membership of the European Union and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
The deal was approved by the Czech Chamber of Deputies (lower
house of parliament) on February 14. Germany's Bundestag
(parliament) approved the declaration on January 30. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
