<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Joblessness Hits New High in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany's joblessness rose slightly
to another postwar record of 4,672 million last month following a
dramatic jump in January.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Labour Office said today that some 13,600 more
people were out of work in February than in January, but the
increase did not change the unemployment rate which stood at 12.2
percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment figure dropped by 8,200 in western Germany to
just under 3.26 million, or 10.6 percent of the workforce.
</P>
<P>
But in the eastern part of the country, it surged 21,800 to
over 1.41 million, a rate of 18.9 percent, the office said.
</P>
<P>
Bernhard Jagoda, president of the Federal Labour Office, said
the fact that joblessness rose only slightly in February did not
reduce the urgency for action.
</P>
<P>
"The challenge remains unalterably great," he said, adding that
there were no simple answers to the employment crisis.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the gloomy picture, a report issued Thursday by
the Federal Statistics Office in Wiesbaden showed that Germany
lost a total of 504,000 jobs during 1996, one fourth of them in
eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, an average of 36.51 million people had
jobs in 1991 while last year's average stood at 34.47 million,
which means more than two million have been lost over the five-year
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reemployment Program to Benefit Unemployed (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- While many workers who are laid
off by China's money-losing state sector have no idea where to
find new jobs, local officials at the ongoing NPC session have
brought with them some good news: more job opportunities thanks to
a nationwide reemployment program.
</P>
<P>
"As long as localities and enterprises can make optimal use of
resources instead of waiting for job opportunities, the laid-off
can be reemployed," said Teng Zhaoxiang, party secretary of Yichun
City, Heilongjiang Province, which was once troubled by
100,000-plus unemployed.
</P>
<P>
A city known for having the country's largest lumbering
industry, Yichun relied heavily on timber production. The city of
1.34 million people has been obliged to cut down timber output
since the 1990s following new restrictions on logging.
As a result, more than 32 percent of its 380,000 lumberjacks
lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
In the government report by Premier Li Peng, forestry industry
is listed as one of the five which are operating at a big loss or
experiencing great difficulties, along with textile, coal,
machinery and weapons industries.
</P>
<P>
To provide more jobs for the laid-off, Yichun City has offered
preferential policies encouraging the unemployed to go into
production, processing and sales of local mountain products as
well as crop production and livestock raising.
</P>
<P>
According to Teng Zhaoxiang, some 17,000 unemployed workers
were reemployed in 1996 and another 30,000 will be employed this
year. All laid-offs in the city's timber industry are expected to
be reemployed in three years.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing Iron and Steel Complex is another enterprise which
has successfully carried out the reemployment program. According
to Ge Daiyi, the general manager, 34,000 out of the factory's iron
and steel workers were transferred to such trades as construction,
machine-building, transportation and catering industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Yan, a woman laid off by the Chongqing factory, traveled
3,000 km to the northeast city of Harbin to serve Sichuan cuisine.
She is so successful today that she has started eight chain stores
there with 40 million yuan in annual revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Firms to Continue Job Cuts Despite High Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Many German firms plan to continue
shedding labor this year despite record post-war unemployment of
4.67 million in February, according to a survey published today by
the German Council of Trade and Industry (DIHT).
</P>
<P>
The survey of 25,000 German firms revealed that more than 30
percent of companies plan to reduce their workforce with only 10
percent planning to hire more workers.
</P>
<P>
In western Germany, a third of the firms expect to make job
cuts and 57 percent plan to maintain their current work force,
while in eastern Germany, 30 percent are planning cuts and 60
percent keeping employment at the present level during 1997.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics released today showed that unemployment
rose slightly to a new high of 4,672 million in February after a
dramatic jump in January.
</P>
<P>
The February joblessness was 13,600 higher than January's 4.66
million, while the rate remained unchanged at 12.2 percent, said
the Nuremberg-based Federal Labor Office, which tabulates the
monthly jobs data.
</P>
<P>
While the German economy was expected to benefit this year from
foreign demand, low interest rates and low inflation, the DIHT
noted that high unemployment would continue to strangle domestic
demand, which is needed to boost the economy.
</P>
<P>
The German government has forecast gross domestic product (GDP)
growth of 2.5 percent this year, after 1.4 percent growth in
1996. But many economists are sceptical about the forecast.
</P>
<P>
Zero GDP growth in the fourth quarter of 1996 and economists'
projections of a 0.25 percent increase for the first quarter this
year have raised doubts about the economy's prospects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
