<HEADLINE> Chinese Short-Track Speed Skaters Tested Free of Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- All Chinese short-track speed
skaters were tested negative for illegal drugs in the span of last
October to January, it was announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 skaters who will take part in the two-day
short-track speedskating competition of the China's Eighth
National Games on Friday and Saturday were tested by the
Anti-Doping Center of the Games, said Guo Ruiju, secretary of the
Chinese Skating Association.
</P>
<P>
"The anti-doping center conducted more than 50 tests by three
times, including two out-of-competition tests," Guo said.
</P>
<P>
But Guo didn't unclose the names tested, saying that all top
skaters had undergone the tests.
</P>
<P>
Li Jiajun, who won the men's 1,000 meters in the 1996 world
championships, and Wang Chunlu, winner of the women's 500 and
1,000 meters races and 3,000 meters relay in the 1995 world
championships, are among the medal favorites in the two-day event.
</P>
<P>
Chinese short-track speed skaters has no record of using banned
substances and will have further tests during the National Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
