<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprise Managers Need Motivation: Deputies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China should accelerate the pace
of setting up a mechanism aimed at both motivating and restraining
managers of state-owned enterprises, according to deputies to the
National People's Congress (NPC), the legislature, which is in
session here.
</P>
<P>
The deputies described a lack of accountability on the part of
executives of state firms by quoting a popular comment to the
effect that "there are at present only factory directors who jump
the ship for another and no factory directors who jump out of the
window (to commit suicide)."
</P>
<P>
Huang Guancong, a deputy from a Shanghai electronics company,
said: "Without responsible managers, state-owned enterprises
cannot be rejuvenated even with the best of external conditions."
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, China must set up a motivation and
restraint system, under which those who perform well are rewarded
and those who do not are penalized, he said.
</P>
<P>
The key to resolving the problem lies in establishing a system
that pegs the interests of business managers and factory directors
to the performance of their enterprises, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Xu Zhiyi, director of the Shanghai Municipal Economic
Commission, said that the basis for such a mechanism is to foster
a contingent of market-oriented and professional enterprise
managers.
</P>
<P>
"This calls for greater effort on the part of economic and
personnel departments of the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Wei Guangai, a trade union official of another Shanghai
company, said that the responsibility of the managers of small
state-owned share-holding enterprises are strengthened partly due
to the fact that they are elected by workers and are subject
to supervision by workers conferences.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
