<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Proposes Building Information Security System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese expert today suggested
that China build its own information security system.
</P>
<P>
Professor Qian Jingren from the Chinese University of Science
and Technology made the suggestion when attending the current
session of the Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference, China's top advisory body.
</P>
<P>
China plans to promote the development of electronic and
information technologies, said its minister in charge of the State
Planning Commission at the current session.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of an information security system is an
important part of this process, Professor Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Qian, an expert on electromagnetic field theories and microwave
technologies, said the explosive information flow brought by the
Internet indicates that the human race has entered the information
age, and network security begins to stand out as an issue meriting
serious attention.
</P>
<P>
Problems concerning security include computer virus, steal of
secret information, on-line fraud, transmission of unhealthy
information, and attempts to subvert other countries through
information transmission, explained the professor.
</P>
<P>
China is making fast progress in the information field. There
were only 2,100 computers linked up with the Internet at the end
of 1995, which sprang five-fold to 11,000 in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
To better develop information resources, Qian proposed that
China follow the example of other countries in enacting laws and
regulations on information security, strengthening management, and
make legislative and judicial explanations.
</P>
<P>
He suggested China increase research on key technologies and
equipment for a high-speed information network when introducing
foreign-made hardware and software, and formulate policies aimed
at protecting the national information industry.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the vast majority of China's high-speed
information networks have been built with imported technologies,
with most information flowing on them originating from overseas,
too.
</P>
<P>
"A more important thing is to learn to publicize China's own
national culture, achievements in economic development, and
industrial and agricultural products, and to develop its own
information resources in a well-organized way," Qian noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
