<HEADLINE> Palestinian Minister Blasts Israeli Provocations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian Minister of Islamic
Waqf Hasan Tahboub said today recent Israeli practices in East
Jerusalem are meant to provoke Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egyptian Voice of Arab radio, he said
Israel's decision to close down four Palestinian institutions in
East Jerusalem is a provocative measure and reflects Israel's
continued attempt to Judaize the holy city by expanding settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
The minister also refuted the Israeli claim that Jews own most
of Har Homa, a tree-covered hill in East Jerusalem, where Israel
decided to build 6,500 Jewish homes soon.
</P>
<P>
"Jerusalem is occupied land on which the U.N. Security Council
resolution 242 is applied and occupation authorities have no right
to make any changes in occupied parts," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu said here Wednesday
during a visit to Egypt that 70 percent of Har Homa Mount is
"private Jewish land." He complained that the whole issue has been
"overblown."
</P>
<P>
Asked about Netanyahu's rejection of setting up a Palestinian
state with Jerusalem as its capital, Tahboub noted that outcome of
peace negotiations are not hinged on what the Israeli leader says
and that the peace process will continue.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians are capable to declare the establishment of
their country with Jerusalem as its capital," he added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat, angry
over the Israeli decision which he deemed as a violation of Oslo
agreements, has threatened to declare the Palestinian state if
Netanyahu goes through with the Har Homa project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
