<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Studies on Keichousaurus Stressed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China will conduct a large-scale
excavation this year to search for fossils of the Keichousaurus, a
creature that lived in shallow seawater some 200 million years ago
in what is now southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
The lizard-like creature, which looks like a miniature
dinosaur, dates from the middle of the Triassic period, some 100
million years earlier than the dinosaur epoch.
</P>
<P>
Over the next three years, Chinese scientists will study the
evolution of the Keichousaurus, its living environment, and the
cause of its extinction. Restoration of fossils also will be done
during that time.
</P>
<P>
First found in 1957 in Xingyi, Keichousaurus fossils have
become targets for smugglers in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The city government confiscated some 700 of the illegally-dug
fossils, of which 226 have been appraised as rare relics.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Xijin, who was in charge of the appraisal and is a
palaeontologist with the Institute of Vertebrate Palaeontology and
Palaeoanthropology under the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said
that Keichousaurus fossils were found among fossils of other
ancient vertebrates such as the nothosauria, the peltopleurus and
the sinoeugnathus.
</P>
<P>
He said that these are the first reptile and fish fossils found
together in the same marine deposit.
</P>
<P>
There still exist many missing links in the organic evolution
of these remote ages, Zhao said, and any discoveries of an unknown
species "can fill in a blank." He added that palaeontological
fossils are rare in the world, so the findings at Xingyi are "all
the more precious."
</P>
<P>
A conservation area covering eight km has been set up at the
site where the fossils were found. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
