<HEADLINE> CPPCC Convenes Third Meeting (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The fifth session of the Eighth
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference, the country's top advisory body, convened its third
plenary meeting in the Great Hall of the People this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The executive chairmen of the meeting were Wu Xueqian, Sun
Fuling and Henry Fok Ying-tung, who are all vice chairmen of the
CPPCC National Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Tienong, a member of the Standing Committee of the CPPCC
National Committee and vice-chairman of the Central Committee of
the Revolutionary Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang, proposed
the establishment of a system by which all youngsters are
obliged to offer free services on a voluntary basis, to help them
raise their ideological and moral standards.
</P>
<P>
Services include helping the aged and respecting the old,
helping the disabled and the weak, contributing to the effort to
wipe out illiteracy and poverty, protecting the environment, and
others.
</P>
<P>
Jin Kaicheng, vice-chairman of the Central Committee of the Jiu
San (September 3 ) Society, said that in the process of
establishing and improving a socialist market economic system,
effort should be made to publicize and carry forward the lofty
ideal of "serving the people."
</P>
<P>
"Serving the people" requires all enterprises participating in
market activities to provide receivers with commodities and
services of fine quality at rational prices, Jin said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Meng, vice-chairman of the Chinese Writers' Association,
said: " We should build China into a cultural power while
persisting in focusing on economic construction."
</P>
<P>
He proposed encouraging both Chinese and foreigners to learn
Chinese and Chinese characters and paying greater attention to
standardizing the Chinese language and Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
Effort should also be made to protect and sort out ancient
books and records, carry forward the Chinese culture, promote the
influence of Chinese culture throughout the world, among others,
Wang said.
</P>
