<HEADLINE> Sichuan To Heavily Invest in Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan Province
will invest 6.1 billion yuan (about 735 million US dollars) in the
fixed assests of its telecommunications industry, aiming at
further strengthening its leading position in the forthcoming
telecom take-off in the inland southwest.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of China Electronics News said that the
province intends to increase the business incomes of posts and
telecommunications by 36 percent this year, hitting 7.17 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The huge investment will be used to launch 3,500 km of optical
cables, acquire 20,000 terminals of long-distance switching
capacity, install 7,000 long-distance transmission systems with a
speed of 2Gb/s, and expand the local telephone switching capacity
by one million lines, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the province will complete the first-phase expansion
project on the digital and data network (DDN), and add more than
15,000 channels to its mobile telephone network this year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the telephone availability rate will reach
3.43 percent in Sichuan, and 55 percent of the phone calls will
get through at the first dial.  
</P>
</TEXT>
