<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Provinces to Seek Sound Economic Structuring (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Provinces and municipalities
across China are either pondering over problems in economic
development or revising draft plans in a bid to put an end to
repetitive construction, which has cost losses of up to one
billion US dollars in China.
</P>
<P>
In the current session of the National People's Congress, local
leaders are convinced that the root cause of surplus production
capacity and debt-ridden state sector lies in indulging in
building large and all-inclusive enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Although Premier Li Peng's proposal for economic restructuring
would result in some conflicts of interests between the central
and local governments and between different parts of China, local
officials are convinced that it is still a pressing task for China
to further improve economic structure and ensure a long-term and
healthy economic development.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, about 93 percent of China's
industrial sectors resemble one another from one place to another.
There are more than 130 automotive plants across China, more than
the world's total.
</P>
<P>
In his report delivered at the on-going NPC session, Premier Li
Peng voiced the pledge of the Chinese government to "strictly
control" the launching of ordinary processing projects. "No
project will get approval if production capacity in that field is
already excessive, " he said.
</P>
<P>
He also reiterated his call for what he termed "structural
readjustment", already a catch phrase in the Ninth Five-Year Plan
and Long-Range Objective Through the year 2010, saying "not" to
launch new projects if existing capacity can be utilized in
reorganizing or transformating them.
</P>
<P>
Local officials voiced consent to Li's view. "If China does not
alterr this situation, it will possibly have a new round of
repetitive construction in a bigger scale and with more
investment," they said. All localities should take into account
long-term interests of the national development instead of their
immediate interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Provinces to Seek Sound Economic Structure (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zheng Silin, governor of east China's Jiangsu province, one of
the country's top economic powerhouses, offered his endorsement to
the central policy.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Jiangsu, which has a wealth of professionals but
a scarcity in natural resources, its development should be
concentrated on high and new technology sector, service industry,
and basic infrastructure and facilities, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
Lu Ruihua, governor of south China's Guangdong province which
has been in the forefront of reform and opening-up, acknowledged
that his province has erred to put automaking at the top of its
pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
"Guangdong does not have any advantages in national
distribution of auto industry, and so we shall not make related
efforts this year," Lu noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that the province has decided to put emphasis on the
light, textiles, and hi-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning province,northeast China, has been a traditional
industrial base, with the prop of heavy and chemical industries.
</P>
<P>
Although there is no need for major readjustment of the
structure since Liaoning is expected to continue focusing on the
petrochemical, metallurgical, machinery and electronic industries,
the province still have a major task to upgrade its outdated
technologies and equipment and product mix, said Governor Wen
Shizhen.
</P>
<P>
Central and western region are likely to be the biggest winner
in this structuring drive. Thanks to the preferential policies
granted by the central government to reduce the gap between the
region and the eastern part of the country, experts say, the
region will have an opportunity to obtain new investment to
develop its resources-related industries.
</P>
<P>
With its salt, metals and petroleum and other abundant natural
reserves, Qinghai province on the Qinghai-Tibet plateau has strong
potential in making it a national base for the chemical and
nonferrous-metal industries, said Governor Tian Chengping.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Governor He Zhiqiang of tropical Yunnan province
said that his province plans to go in for the tobacco industry,
mineral and biological resources development, and tourist
industry.
</P>
<P>
The provincial governors held that readjustment of the economic
structure will be a long and changing process, since it is
inevitable that micro and macro interests, and local and overall
interests often conflict one another.
</P>
<P>
The economic restructuring should be sped up, and macroeconomic
measures improved, so as to give full scope to the leading role of
the market. And this is the an important guarantee for a healthy
development of the national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
