<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Uses More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province, an economic powerhouse in China, reported steady growth
in the use of overseas investment in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the province approved nearly 6,000 contracts involving
the use of overseas funds, with the amount of such funds totaling
17.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has brought in 750 million dollars in overseas
investment since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The actual amount of overseas funds flowing into Guangdong last
year increased by 14 percent, though the number of contracts and
contractual value decreased.
</P>
<P>
Direct investment was the principal form in the province,
making up 80 or 90 percent of the amount involved in contracts
signed last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of projects built exclusively with foreign funds
exceeded that of joint ventures and cooperative projects for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
The production scale of foreign-funded projects has expanded,
with each averaging 3.37 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of investment from Hong Kong and Macao has continued
to slide, while that from Western Europe, North America and
Oceania has increased by a big margin.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry
and fishery increased by 87 percent last year and the investment
in technology-intensive industries rose 50 percent compared with
the year before. 
</P>
