<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa's Row with West over Ivory Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa's simmering
argument with the West on ivory trade will continue until the
10th Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species
(CITES) set for June 9-20 here makes a decision.
</P>
<P>
All southern African countries now demand the resumption of
the trade of ivory and other elephant products while some western
animal rights groups are trying hard to oppose it, describing the
move as murderous.
</P>
<P>
The proposal on resuming ivory trade was first put forward by
Zimbabwe, Botswana and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state and government of the 12-member Southern
African Development Community (SADC) approved the proposal in
their summit in Maseru, Lesotho last August to downlist the
status of the African elephant from current Appendix I to
Appendix II.
</P>
<P>
Wild animals in Appendix I of the Convention are not allowed
to be utilized, while those in Appendix II can be sustainably
utilized.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, if the status of African elephant is transferred
from Appendix I to Appendix II, the southern African countries
will be allowed to export registered stocks of raw tusks of ivory
to one trading partner.
</P>
<P>
In response, western animal rights groups are using their
political votes to put pressure on their governments to stop
helping organizations they label as supporters of the killing of
animals.
</P>
<P>
They have even extended their influence to donors involved in
the region, asking them to cut aid to countries defying their
dictates.
</P>
<P>
The Humane Society of the United States (HSUS), a major animal
rights group, is reportedly campaigning for discrediting Communal
Areas Management Program for Indigenous Resources of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The HSUS is also attempting to halt the funding for the
program from the U.S. Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the West is seeking to change the 10th CITES venue
from Zimbabwe to another country supporting the ban so as to get
a favorable CITES decision.
</P>
<P>
About 1,500 delegates from 136 countries around the world are
expected to attend the conference.
</P>
<P>
Countries in southern Africa argued that unlike some areas on
the continent where elephants might face a danger of extinction
due to poaching and mismanagement of wildlife resources, southern
Africa has seen so huge an elephant population that it is now
causing a serious animal-human conflict.
</P>
<P>
Elephant in most parts of southern Africa is not an endangered
species, instead, it poses actually a danger to the region's
environment and human life because the significant increase of
their number is now out of control, said SADC government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Director of Communal Areas Management Program for Indigenous
Resources of Zimbabwe Taparendave Maveneke noted that the number
of elephants are rising immensely in southern Africa and
constitute threats to the survival of other wild species and the
whole ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has a herd of at least 65,000 elephants while its
carrying capacity is less than 30,000, he asserted.
</P>
<P>
People living in elephant-rich areas are trampled upon by the
huge mammal to death or maimed for life now and then, leaving
constant fear among residents there. Children are afraid of going
to school in these areas.
</P>
<P>
Houses damaged or crops and natural vegetation destroyed by
elephants are frequent stories carried in newspapers in the
countries in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Since the ban on ivory trade in 1989, Zimbabwe has stockpiled
40 tons of ivory and lost 29 million U.S. Dollars in revenue.
</P>
<P>
The country will continue to lose about 500,000 U.S. Dollars
annually, Zimbabwean wildlife experts said.
</P>
<P>
The lost money could have benefited the cash-strapped national
parks department and other official social welfare programs in
the country, some Zimbabwean wildlife experts pointed out. "The
West puts animals before human beings," they complained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
