<HEADLINE> Kenya Launchs Urban Roads Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has decided
to rehabilitate urban roads at a cost of almost 150 million U.S.
Dollars to improve transport infrastructure management and its
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Local Government Minister Francis Lotodo launched here
Wednesday the Kenya Urban Transport Infrastructure Project which
is jointly funded by the World Bank and the Kenyan government.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank will provide about 110 million Dollars and the
remaining will be allocated by the Kenyan government.
</P>
<P>
The project will cover Nairobi and 25 other cities and towns
in the eastern African country, where major physical work will
begin from mid-May.
</P>
<P>
At the launching ceremony, World Bank representative Harold
Wackman said his bank was involved in the project after a study
had found out that less than 10 percent of urban roads in Kenya
were in good state.
</P>
<P>
He called for regular maintenance of infrastructure, adding
that the present rehabilitation work would not have been
necessary if the roads have been under regular maintenance.
</P>
