been registered for the March 15 local government elections on
party basis, the Guardian newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figure is 18.8 million more than the 41.8 million voters
registered for the 1993 polls, according to a "tentative
computation" by the National Electoral Commission of Nigeria
(NECON) of last month's voters' registration.
</P>
<P>
NECON has identified 1.4 million registered names as
fictitious, stemming from multiple registration and listing of
under-aged persons, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics by the United Nations put the population
of Nigeria at 115 million by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The National Population Commission said in its report on the
final 1991 census that 45 percent of the country's population are
under age 15 and only three percent above the age of 64.
</P>
<P>
The eligible age for registration is 18 in the western African
country.
</P>
<P>
The census report has been submitted to Nigeria's head of
state General Sani Abacha recently.
</P>
<P>
NECON sources described the turnout of the registration as
"impressive", saying that it shows the enthusiasm of the people
toward the government's transition to civil rule program. 
