<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beads for Calculation At Least 2,700 Years Old </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Eighty-six clay beads from the
Western Zhou Dynasty (11th Century-771 BC) have been identified as
those used for calculation, which dates the origin of the abacus
to at least 2,700 years ago.
</P>
<P>
It was previously believed that the abacus was developed in the
Eastern Han Dynasty (25-220), based on the earliest record about
it found in an arithmetic book from that period.
</P>
<P>
The beads, in green, yellow or white, were found in 1978 among
the palace remains at the Zhouyuan site in Baoji, northwest
China's Shaanxi Province, the birthplace of the Zhou people who
established the Zhou Dynasty (11th Century-221 BC).
</P>
<P>
Mostly round, the beads have a diameter of two cm and bear
traces of knife-cuts, polishing, and fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
No theories on the use of the beads had been put forward until
1984, when two local experts published theses claiming that the
beads were probably used for calculation.
</P>
<P>
Their conclusion was recently approved at a symposium held by
leading archaeologists in the province and the country's top
experts on the history of abacus.
</P>
<P>
The experts ruled out the possibilities of the beads being used
as toys, money, or a traditional Chinese medical instrument. They
say that the beads, including two on which are symbols related to
calculation, can be verified as the genuine originals.
</P>
<P>
The beads are identical to information in historical records
about the first beads for figuring numbers, which were green,
yellow or white, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, the different colored beads
each represent certain digits: green stands for 9, 6, and 3;
yellow for 8, 5, and 2; and white, 7, 4, and 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
