<HEADLINE> More Hidden Arms Found in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The West African peace-keeping
force (ECOMOG) operating in Liberia has uncovered some weapons
hidden by ex-fighters who said they formerly belonged to Charles
Taylor's National Patriotic Front of Liberia (NPFL).
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here today, heavily armed
ECOMOG troops discovered on Tuesday the huge mass of weapons and
arrested 15 people linked to the arms found 45 kilometers north
of Monrovia, the Liberian capital.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time this week that arms allegedly concealed
by former rival factions were brought into light, only a month
after most arms held by ex-fighters were urged to be handed over
to ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an ECOMOG statement as saying that the
weapons had been dug up in an abandoned mining town of Bungami,
formerly under the control of the defunct NPFL.
</P>
<P>
The weapons that were put on display on Wednesday included
dozens of rifles and machine guns, which were rusty and covered
in dirts.
</P>
<P>
The arrested described themselves as former NPFL fighters,
saying that the weapons had been buried by their commanders two
weeks before the disarmament exercise.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, a former NPFL captain who has fled to Cote
d'Ivoire alleged that his ex-fellow fighters hid some weapons
from ECOMOG, which supervised the disarmament program.
</P>
<P>
However, Taylor denied the charges, saying that it was a
propaganda aimed at setting ECOMOG against him.
</P>
<P>
"There may be bigger hands behind this one but those hands are
going to fail. ECOMOG must win this war," Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
He also alleged that indications show there are some external
forces whose aim is to destabilize the forthcoming election and
probably delay it for two to three years.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, ECOMOG announced that it had uncovered a
large weapon cache buried at a diamond depository. The cache
included assorted rifles and rocket propelled grenades during a
raid following information received from the public.
</P>
<P>
The weapons were found at Lofa bridge, about 60 kilometers
west of Monrovia which was contested by the former United
Liberation Movement (ULIMO) factions before the disarmament
exercise.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of such huge quantity of weapons has tightened
the security situation in Monrovia. All vehicles are being
vigorously searched there and people are questioned if they
demonstrate unusual attitude, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Liberian peace process is currently progressing
toward general elections scheduled for May this year after the
successful disarmament of the formal warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Charles Taylor and two other major former factional leaders,
Alhaji Kromah and George Boley, have resigned from the ruling
Council of State to contest for the presidency in the forthcoming
national polls.
</P>
<P>
All three were former vice-chairmen of the interim government.
</P>
</TEXT>
