<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading British newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Major held out the prospect of a
tax-free pension of 175 pounds (about 280 U.S. dollars) a week for
the next generation on Wednesday when he unveiled plans for the
biggest overhaul in state pensions for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- British Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind Wednesday
described as "very worrying" the fact that the Middle East and
North Africa received only 4 percent of global private capital
flows compared with Asia's 60 percent share and Latin America's 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- An alarming unpublished report raised fears a year ago that
poor slaughterhouse hygiene was increasing the risk of infection
from the E-coli bacterium, which later killed 20 people in
Scotland, it emerged Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The Independent
</P>
<P>
-- Pressure mounted on the two biggest British tobacco
companies to settle claims from lung cancer victims on Wednesday
after BAT, a major American cigarette-maker, held out the prospect
of a multi-billion pound settlement with thousands of smokers in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- A second British defense minister apologized Wednesday for
misleading Parliament over the extent to which pesticides blamed
for Gulf War syndrome were used in the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
