<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Louis Schweitzer, boss of the French automaker Renault, was
asked Wednesday by Prime Minister Alain Juppe to engage rapidly in
consultation with the staff of Renault's Vilvoorde assembly plant
in Belgium. But the prime minister did not ask him to cancel his
plan to close the Vilvoorde plant and lay off 2,764 workers in
France.
</P>
<P>
-- A typhus epidemic is hitting all parts of Burundi and
threatening 500,000 refugees with death. Between 500 and 1,000
typhus cases are reported each day in the refugee camps in the
provinces of Muramvya, Kayanza and N'Gozi. French scientists
described the typhus epidemic as the most massive ever seen after
World War II.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The plan of the far-right National Front (FN) party to hold
its congress this weekend in Strasbourg has caused a dispute in
Alsace, where some 15,000 people have signed an appeal for
protests against the FN.
</P>
<P>
-- The United States is trying to shelve the issue of
Europeanization of the Naples-based Southern Command of NATO. The
United States Defense Secretary William Cohen said in Bonn this
week that Washington will re-examine the problem five, six or
seven years later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
