<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Signs Communique to Avoid Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan Wednesday night made a U-turn by signing a 22-point
communique of the military-dominated National Security Council
(NSC) against the coalition led by pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP),
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, who had been in confrontation with the military for
some days on the issue of secularism, was believed to have made
concession for the fate of his coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign minister Tansu Ciller gave
in under the military pressure and then persuaded her partner to
sign the communique to avoid the discontinuation of the alliance
between the RP and the True Path Party (DYP) that she chairs
herself.
</P>
<P>
Ciller reportedly said that she was under pressure from
both the military and her own party and asked Erbakan to
put a signature on the communique for the continuation of the
present coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The military led by Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki
Karadayi worked out the 22-point communique designed to curb the
rising "fundamentalist" activities to the coalition
government following the February 28 meeting of the NSC.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion held that this was an "ultimatum" to the
RP from the military which has long been defending Turkey's
secular system.
</P>
<P>
The NSC meeting, chaired by President Suleyman Demirel and
attended by powerful civilian and military leaders, was called
as a result of a increasing threat directed at the secular
system of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Recent proposals by the Welfare Party led by Erbakan on
ordering women civil servants to wear Islamic-style head covering
and building a mosque in one of the main commercial squares in
Istanbul, the largest city of the country, triggered strong
criticism from Western-oriented Turks, especially the military.
</P>
<P>
A religious rally called "Jerusalem Night" held on February
1 in Sincan city, 40 kilometers west of Ankara, also caused
serious concern over the increase of the "fundamentalist" force
in the secular republic.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan has maintained a hard stance until Tuesday when he
sent back a senior general who brought the military-proposed
recommendations for his endorsement, leading to speculation that
a political crisis would be imminent.
</P>
<P>
However, the Islamist prime minister reversed his stance
after his junior partner Ciller threatened to discontinue her
cooperation with the Welfare Party.
</P>
<P>
Ciller was quoted by local press as telling Erbakan that
"you should withdraw from the government if you don't sign
the communique."
</P>
<P>
Under the all-out help of her coalition partner, Ciller
averted several parliamentary ballots aimed at bringing her to
the Supreme Court to stand for trial on corruption charges, and
she is believed to continue seeking for protection under the RP
umbrella.
</P>
<P>
Although Erbakan has signed the communique, the opposition has
no plan of stopping their confrontation with his Islamist party.
</P>
<P>
Some opposition leaders, including Mesut Yilmaz, Chairman of
the Motherland Party, would not like to let the opportunity
slip by calling for the resignation of the coalition government.
</P>
</TEXT>
