<HEADLINE> National Contest on Reciting Koran Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A four-day national Koran
recitation contest ended here today, with first prize in the men's
category going to Yilias from the Xinjiang Autonomous Region, and
Ma Peiying from the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region taking top
honors in the women's competition.
</P>
<P>
This was the second such contest held by the China Islamic
Association. The first was in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, 106 Moslems from 24 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions across the country, most of whom are young
people, participated in preliminary contests, and 46 people,
including six women, were selected to take part in the final
contest.
</P>
<P>
Attending the event were More than 200 people, including
officials from several central government departments related to
religious and ethnic affairs, ambassadors in China from Saudi
Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Iran and Oman, as well as those
from the Islamic community throughout China.
</P>
<P>
The contest is aimed at choosing and cultivating Chinese
Moslems who are skilled at reciting the Koran in accordance with
established rules, said Muhammad Al-Hanafi, vice-chairman and vice
secretary-general of the China Islamic Association.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the Koran is the most fundamental and revered
classic of Islam.
</P>
<P>
Since the last contest, 15 Moslems have been chosen to recite
the Koran in Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Iran and Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
