<HEADLINE> Rebel's Armory Found in N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Uganda official army has
discovered a rebel armory in a no man's area in northern Uganda,
a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Colonel James Kazini, the commander of the fourth division of
Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF), told The New Vision that
the ammunition discovered in the north of Ngom Oromo, Kitgum
District include 25 anti-tank land mines and 45 boxes of bullets.
</P>
<P>
The ammunition had been transported from Sudan by 300 rebels
of the Christian Lord Resistance Army (LRA) who vowed to topple
the government and was hidden in six holes dug in the ground for
the next LRA offensive, the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
A former LRA member defecting to UPDF after the main forces of
his group had fled into Sudan informed UPDF of the batch of
ammunition and led government troops to the spot, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The major LRA remnants now retreat to their bases and find
shelters in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
LRA once had 2,000 soldiers in its ranks but now has only
hundreds of fighters, claimed the report.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Kony, the LRA leader, is proposing to have peace talks
between LRA and the government.
</P>
<P>
However, Kintu Musoke, the Ugandan prime minister, told
parliament Wednesday that the government had decided to continue
the fight to quell LRA rebels.
</P>
<P>
Previous experiences indicate that Kony's suggestion for peace
talks is only a cover and an excuse for preparing another round
of fierce fighting, he said. Endiem

