<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Proposals Made on Enhancing Management of Migrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A member of China's top advisory
body today proposed legislation enhancing administration of the
country's large migrating population in an orderly way.
</P>
<P>
"A law concerning migration should be promulgated as soon as
possible," Mei Xiangming, vice-chairman of the China Association
for Promoting Democracy, said at a meeting of the ongoing fifth
session of the Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
Given the fact that it will take some time to formulate a law,
the State Council may first issue a set of regulations on the
administration of migrating population, Mei said.
</P>
<P>
The member also set forth some other proposals relevant to
the issue.
</P>
<P>
He urged officials at all levels to take the issue of migrating
population as a major subject of promoting socialist material and
socialist ethical and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
Labor market information should be released on a regularly
basis to help those who want to find jobs or do business away from
their hometowns make correct choices, he said. The administrative
departments should also organize and provide technical trainings
for the migrant workers based on market demand.
</P>
<P>
Mei went on to say that those floating people without essential
certificates should be sent back to their hometowns, and high
charges for residence, environmental protection and urban
management should be levied on their jobless family members.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, all-round services should be provided to those with
necessary certificates that have paid the required fees, including
providing the necessary conditions for the children of the
migrants to attend schools, the member said, adding that the
system of residence permits should be reformed.
</P>
<P>
Education of the migrants should also be strengthened so as to
help them foster a correct outlook on both life and value, Mei
said.
</P>
<P>
So far, experts have put China's migrating population at more
than 120 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
