<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Arrives on State Visit to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 6 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela arrived here this afternoon on a five-day state
visit to Malaysia, the last leg of his four-nation Southeast Asian
tour.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, accompanied by an 115-member delegation comprising
officials and businessmen, was received by Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad at the Kuala Lumpur International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had already visited the Philippines, Brunei and
Singapore, all being members of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
During his first state visit here since he became South
Africa's head of state, Mandela is scheduled to have an audience
with Malaysian King Tuanku Ja'afar and hold talks with Mahathir,
focusing on bilateral, regional and international issues of common
concern.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is also scheduled to deliver a keynote address at the
Institute of Diplomacy and Foreign Relations on "South Africa and
Malaysia -- A Joint Vision Towards the 21st Century" and another
at the Second South Africa-Malaysia Business Forum.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who turns 79 in July, would highlight areas or
potentials in South Africa that could be tapped by Malaysian
investors such as in property development, privatization projects
and tourism, according to official sources here.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and South Africa will sign a number of agreements
during Mandela's visit which was aimed at strengthening bilateral
ties and economic cooperation, according to the sources here who
however declined to name what the pacts would be.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia established diplomatic relations with South Africa in
November 1993.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is now a major trading partner of South Africa in this
region with total trade amounting to 883 million ringgit (about
353.2 million U.S. dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made two trips to Malaysia before the all-party South
African election in 1994. He forged close personal ties with
Mahathir who made an unofficial stop-over in South Africa in 1992
and his first official visit to South Africa in August 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
