<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Reviews Amendments to Criminal Law  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Draft amendments to bring sweeping
changes to the country's 17-year-old criminal code were submitted
to the Fifth Session of the Eighth National People's Congress,
China's top legislative body, for deliberation today.
</P>
<P>
The 1979 criminal law comprising 192 articles is to be revised
into 449 articles, with a total of 257 articles added, according
to Wang Hanbin, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, who
made an explanation on the draft amendments at today's third
plenary meeting of the NPC session.
</P>
<P>
China is trying to work out "a unified and fairly complete
penal code through the revision," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"It will represent a major step forward in improving our
country's penal system and judicial system, and will be of
important significance for making further progress in the rule of
law and in building a socialist legal system," he said.
</P>
<P>
The tasks and basic principles as defined in the existing law
are correct and will not be altered, he said.
</P>
<P>
But some stipulations in the law are not specific enough and,
as some crimes have become more serious over the years and new crimes
have emerged, the existing law is no longer suited for the new
situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
So, "it is necessary to amend, make additions to and improve
the criminal law to cater to the practical need of combating
crimes," he explained.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important revisions to the law is to further
clarify three major principles of criminal justice, namely: crimes
and punishment must be judged and meted out in accordance with
specific provisions of the law, all are equal before the law, and
punishment must be commensurate with crimes.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the establishment of the first principle,
provisions on analogy are to be deleted since such provisions
allow courts to judge crimes not defined by the law by referring
to most similar provisions in the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Reviews Amendments to Criminal Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The draft law states that a behavior defined as a crime by the
law shall be convicted and given punishment in accordance with the
law; while behaviors not defined as crimes by the law shall not be
deemed as crime and no punishment shall be meted out.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that "there is the necessity and conditions to
eliminate the analogy provisions" today as the draft contains
specific provisions for various crimes.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, reiteration of the principle of equality of all
before the law in this criminal law has practical significance
despite the fact that it is provided for by the Constitution, the
senior lawmaker said.
</P>
<P>
Counter-revolutionary crimes in the existing law will be
renamed crimes of jeopardizing state security in the draft
amendments. All other crimes not named as crimes of
jeopardizing state security are categorized into crimes of
jeopardizing public security and harming the administration of
social order.
</P>
<P>
Wang explained that, in the existing law, the judgment of some
counter-revolutionary crimes is based on the criterion of
offending "with counterrevolutionary purposes," which is hard to
verify.
</P>
<P>
This revision is made "with the state system and the
safeguarding of overall national interests in mind, and
from a legal point of view," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The draft law contains more detailed provisions on punishment
reduction, release on parole, and punishment whose severity is
below what is prescribed by the law to prevent willful practices
by law-enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
"Justifiable defense" is loosely defined in the existing law
and is prone to lead to willful practices in law enforcement.
Victims and policemen are usually given penalties for defending
themselves under the existing law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Reviews Amendments to Criminal Law (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To protect the rights and interests of victims and
law-enforcement personnel, and encourage chivalry for public
interest, several clauses are added to the law. New provisions
provide, for example, that those causing deaths, injuries and
other consequences as a result of defense against violent acts
that threaten personal safety shall not shoulder criminal
responsibilities; and that on-duty policemen shall be free from
criminal responsibility for using baton or weapons and causing
deaths or injuries in accordance with the law at a time of
violence or with personal safety being threatened.
</P>
<P>
There are new provisions on crimes that have just emerged or
will emerge in the future, such as those committed by the mafia,
organized terrorism, crimes of instigating ethnical hatred or
discrimination, money laundering, computer crimes, securities
frauds and intruding on commercial secrets.
</P>
<P>
Articles on capital punishment are virtually unchanged except
that a stay of execution as the maximum punishment for minors has
been reduced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
Revisions are also made to articles on surrender, meritorious
service, speculation and profiteering, hooliganism, corruption
and malfeasance. Two chapters on violating national defense
interests and violation of duty by armymen are added to the law.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that in the past 17 years, relevant departments have
spent 15 years revising or making additions to the criminal law --
the top legislature has so far promulgated 22 supplementary
provisions and decisions regarding the existing criminal law.
</P>
<P>
The draft law is based mainly on previous legislations and made
by having reference to foreign criminal legislation and world
trends in criminal legislation in a new period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Cooperative Bank Spring Up in Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- More than a hundred Chinese
cities will push their financial reforms forward this year, as a
result of the burgeoning of urban cooperative banks.
</P>
<P>
"Establishing urban cooperative banks based on the former urban
credit cooperatives is a significant measure China has taken to
reform its financial system and commercialize its banking sector,"
said Li Guochen, president of the Urban Cooperative Bank of
Shijiazhuang, a successful example of the experiment in the
northern Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
China first selected 35 cities for the commercialization
try-out last year. Six of them, including Shanghai, Shenzhen,
Shijiazhuang and Nanjing, have so far opened urban cooperative
banks.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the six banks reported smooth operation and
greatly improved credit management. As more strict and unified
controls were imposed on credit extension, the banks' assets
quality was also upgraded.
</P>
<P>
China now has over 5,000 urban credit cooperatives, and the
soon-to-be-restructured local banks will be able to better serve
local medium and small-sized ventures and urban residents, Li said.
</P>
<P>
The Shijiazhuang Urban Cooperative Bank, for example, reported
better economic returns than other special banks in the city since
it opened last May. It also more strongly supported the city's
economic build-up by channeling most of its funds into local key
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
A unified national settlement system has also gone into
operation in Shanghai, hooking up all the six urban cooperative
banks, and speeding up the settlement among different regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
