<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Should Be Encouraged to Produce More Grain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Legislators from China's No. 1
grain producer say special efforts should be made to keep farmers'
enthusiasm in growing grain after the good harvest last year.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Jilin province, northeast China, plan to sell to the
state 16 billion kg of grain this spring, according to Mi Fengjun,
a Jilin deputy to the National People's Congress (NPC), which has
been in session since last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
By February 16, the state had purchased 11 billion kg of grain,
four billion kg more than last year, she said.
</P>
<P>
The top issue now is to prevent the grain from spoiling,
including new grain with a high moisture content that has been
purchased and stored, and the five billion kg of grain waiting to
be purchased by the state, said deputy Zang Shengye.
</P>
<P>
He added that with Jilin's present transport capacity, the
grain cannot be transported out of the province promptly, and the
overflowing of grain storages will affect the purchase of summer
grain.
</P>
<P>
As an expedient measure, the provincial government has
encouraged farmers to reserve the grain still in their own hands,
and made the promise to buy the grain later while granting loans
to farmers for crop raising, said Governor Wang Yunkun who is
attending the NPC session in a non-deputy capacity.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Wang noted, the government has mobilized all
those working in grain reserving departments to sun the grain on
all open ground available to "ensure that not a single grain
goes rotting."
</P>
<P>
The governor added the province planned to expand its grain
storage capacity to 25 billion kg, its grain drying capacity from
the present six billion kg to 15 billion kg, and add new
facilities for grain transport.
</P>
<P>
With 5.3 million hectares of farmland and 25 million farmers,
Jilin has ranked first among all the Chinese provinces and regions
for 11 consecutive years in terms of the amount of grain for each
resident, the amount of commercial grain sold, grain export and
grain sold to other provinces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
