<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICC Conference to Be Held in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- About 1,000 business people,
bankers, economists and officials from over 60 countries and
regions will attend the 32nd Conference of the International
Chamber of Commerce (ICC), to be held in Shanghai from April 7th
through 10th.
</P>
<P>
Under the theme of "Asia in Global Economy", participants of
the conference will discuss the world economy, business in Asia,
the global market in the eyes of Asian business people, China's
role in the world, the Asian economy, and economic development in
Hong Kong and Shanghai, as well as the policy and principles
concerning international commerce.
</P>
<P>
As an important non-governmental international economic and
trade organization, ICC has formulated many business principles
adopted across the world, said Liu Fugui, vice-chairman of ICC
China National Committee.
</P>
<P>
With national committees in 63 countries and members in another
70 countries and regions, ICC is a consultant organ of the United
Nations, which maintains close ties with other international
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The Shanghai Conference will provide an opportunity for the
world to fully understand the Asian economy, especially the
economy of China, as well as a chance for China to see the world,"
Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He added that governmental officials and representatives from
renowned banks and multi-national companies across the world, as
well as China's banks and companies, will address the conference,
which will be sponsored by both ICC and ICC China National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
China joined the ICC at the end of 1994, and established the
national committee in 1995. At present, there are over 200 members
in ICC China National Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0800 GMT, March 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Visiting South African President Nelson Mandela
Wednesday called for "rapid restructuring" of the United Nations
and for vigorous pursuit of the concept of the Indian Ocean Rim
in the process of establishing new world order.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Wednesday expressed support for
the Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) to
send a mission to Albania, where political situation is tense.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Wednesday
discussed the contentious Israeli plan to build a settlement in
east Jerusalem with two top United Nations officials.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Iraq Wednesday called for the United Nations Security
Council to lift the sanctions applied to Iraq since the end of the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The South Korean Defense Ministry announced Thursday
that South Korea and the United States have canceled their annual
joint military exercises for this year, allegedly in a gesture to
ease tensions on the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- In a formal United Nations Security Council
meeting on Wednesday, Israel was urged strongly by member states
to call off its plan to build Jewish settlements in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Members of the U.S. House of Representatives
Wednesday lashed out at the U.S. government's plan to enlarge the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko and Prime Minister
Kengo Wa Dondo have endorsed the United Nations five-point peace
plan for Zaire, Zairean Foreign Minister Gerard Kamanda Wa Kamanda
announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Wednesday criticized Israel for
its shutting down of four Palestinian offices in east Jerusalem,
saying the move was "very difficult to understand." 
</P>
