<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Observers Advised to Take Care of Eyes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Star gazers planning to witness a
total solar eclipse and the Hale-Bopp comet at the same time on
the morning of March 9 are cautioned to take care of their eyes
during the astronomical event.
</P>
<P>
Viewers will be able to see the eclipse in most of the northern
China, Russia, and Mongolia, the last eclipse that can be watched
in China in this century.
</P>
<P>
Hu Zhongwei, associate professor of the astronomy department of
the Nanjing University, suggested that observers be wearing sun
glasses to prevent sun rays from burning the naked eye. Observation
card, black glass, exposed film and other sun-blocking objects
can be used as observation tools for eye protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
