<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African States Seal Capital Market Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda
have signed a memorandum of understanding to form the East
African Securities Regulatory Authorities (EASRA) to coordinate
mutual cooperation in regional capital markets development.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha
on Wednesday by the three eastern African countries (EAC), the
local Daily News paper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Secretariat for EAC capital markets and
securities Paul Melly was quoted as saying that securities
markets are fundamental in boosting private sectors to mobilize
savings and investment, and in promoting efficient resources
allocation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Melly, also the chief executive capital, market authority for
Kenya, said EASRA will deal with technical issues including the
development of the capital markets strategy with the objectives
of mobilizing domestic, regional and international savings for
economic growth of the region.
</P>
<P>
Melly said that the memorandum will strengthen stock exchanges
within the region and planning for development of regional
exchange as well as encouraging cross border listings.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that there will be a common certificate of market
professionals in the region and mutual assistance in the exchange
of information, training, cross border surveillance, supervision,
inspection, investigation and coordination of technical
assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
