<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Approves New Child Support System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The South African cabinet
has approved an additional 1.2 billion Rand (272 million U.S.
Dollars) relief scheme to help three million poor children around
the country over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
All South African children under age six will qualify for a
new benefit if the primary care-giver meets the requirements of a
means test, Welfare and Population Development Minister Geraldine
Fraser-Moleketi was quoted by today's Citizen paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
A simple and workable test that will identify poverty-stricken
households is being finalized, Fraser-Moleketi said.
</P>
<P>
The latest child support system, which will come into
operation on August 1 this year, will be paid at a flat rate of
75 Rand (17 Dollars) for a child per month.
</P>
<P>
The amount has been agreed on because it is slightly above the
household subsistence level for food and clothing for a child
under six years old, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Mothers of babies who obtain the new benefit will be required
to regularly visit primary health care centers and this would
help in monitoring beneficiaries, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The South African Welfare Department currently paid out about
1.2 billion Rand a year in maintenance grants to 349,692
beneficiaries, Fraser-Moleketi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
