<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province Attracting Funds to Fuel Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province in northwest China
expects to attract five billion yuan (about 600 million US
dollars) of overseas investment during the 1996-2000 period to
shore up its power sector.
</P>
<P>
Numerous heavy industries and raw materials resources have long
put a strain on Gansu's electricity supply, which threats to block
the inland province's ambitious development plan.
</P>
<P>
Gansu witnessed a record power shortage of 15 million kwh daily
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
To ease the chronic power shortfall, the province has decided
to add a generating capacity of two million kw to the current five
million kw. Related projects are expected to cost 23.3 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Gansu started ushering overseas capital into the power sector
in 1994 and so far has used 589 million dollars of government and
commercial loans for a dozen projects. The province is currently
building a joint-venture power project -- a 600,000-kw unit in the
Jingyuan Electricity Plant -- with a US company.
</P>
<P>
Before the year 2000, the province plans to revamp two
10-year-old power complexes, the Liancheng Power Plant and the
Bapanxia Hydro-electric Plant, through joint ventures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
