<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Women Have Long Way to Go Before Winning Equality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Canadian women still have a long
way to go before achieving the goal of equality, said a report
released here today by the Canadian Labor Congress (CLC).
</P>
<P>
The 100-page report, on women's career lives in Canada, noted
that only 20 percent of Canadian women have full-time, full-year
jobs, compared to 40 percent of the country's men.
</P>
<P>
It showed that Canada has the second largest number of low-paid
women (34.3 percent) among all industrialized countries except
Japan.
</P>
<P>
And while Canadian women account for less than 20 percent of
those in the top 10 paying job categories, they represent more
than 70 percent in the lowest paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the jobless rate for Canadian women is "shockingly
high" -- 15.6 percent for young women, 13.4 percent for visible
minority women and 17.7 percent for aboriginal women, compared
with the national average of 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Despite women's gains over the last generation, the vast
majority remain stuck in low paying jobs with little hope for
advancement," said CLC Executive Vice-President Nancy Riche.
</P>
<P>
"The myth of women's equality is everywhere...This report
offers a painful reality check to these images," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The Women's Work report indicates that this systematic
discrimination (against women) is not disappearing. Apart from a
small minority of white professional women, women are losing
ground as 'restructuring' by both government and corporations
barrels along," Riche noted.
</P>
<P>
"This is a disgrace for a nation that likes to crow about its
number-one ranking from the United Nations survey on countries'
quality of life," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
