<HEADLINE> Eastern Africa Forms Regional Capital Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda have
signed a memorandum of understanding in Tanzania's northern town
of Arusha for setting up the East African Securities Regulatory
Authorities to enhance their cooperation in capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Capital Markets Authority Chief Executive Paul Melly
was elected the new body's first chairman, according to a Daily
Nation report today.
</P>
<P>
The three eastern African countries agreed to develop a common
capital markets strategy to mobilize domestic, regional and
international savings for developing the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the new body is aimed at strengthening
stock exchange within the region, planning to develop it into a
regional exchange, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
The body will also encourage cross-border listings and the
setting up of a regional rating agency, and train market
professionals with common certification for the region.
</P>
<P>
The heads of the capital markets authorities of the three
countries have agreed to meet after three months to review the
implementation of the memorandum of understanding they signed.
