<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Helping Ethnic Province Eliminate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city, has pledged to help 2.45 million people in
underdeveloped Yunnan Province in southwest China shake off
poverty by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to a newly signed Shanghai-Yunnan poverty relief
agreement, Shanghai is responsible for enabling the poor people
in Simao, Wenshan and Honghe prefectures to have enough food and
clothing, defined as a per capita income 500 yuan and per capita
share of grain above 300 kilograms a year.
</P>
<P>
Specific improvements in drinking water, primary education and
health care are also defined in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The central government has asked the developed eastern areas to
assist the underdeveloped western areas, hoping to balance
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai municipal government has designated 12 of its
districts and counties to support the three prefectures.
</P>
<P>
Personnel training programs are very high on the list. More
than 100 senior managers trained in Shanghai have made significant
progress back in Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Education Commission donated teaching equipment,
and 10.28 million yuan to finance 23 primary schools and an
education fund in Yunnan Province. It trained 570 teachers for the
province last year.
</P>
<P>
The commission also sends experienced teachers, with plans to
establish two teachers training centers in Yunnan to improve the
province's elementary and vocational education programs.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai allocates 10 million yuan annually to set up one or
two key poverty-relief projects in each of the 22 poor counties
concerned.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, determined to tap the resource-rich province's
potential, will help modernize Yunnan's agriculture and animal
husbandry.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to promote the development of township-run
enterprises in Yunnan and help market Yunnan-made products in
Shanghai and other parts of China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
