<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijingers Sign Up to Donate Corneas, Following Deng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Many Beijing residents have signed
up to donate their corneas to an eye bank after death, in tribute
to the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
About 200 to 300 people have filled forms to register at the
Beijing Tongren Eye Bank to donate their corneas since Deng's
request to have his corneas donated was made public on February 20,
the day after the 93-year-old leader died, according to staff
members at the eye bank.
</P>
<P>
"We decide to donate our corneas because this way we can
express our sorrow for Deng's death and show respect to him," said
64-year-old retired official Bu Jinzhi and his wife, Zhang Anqi, a
senior editor at People's Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
"Deng was a great man who gave himself entirely to the country
and the people. We're deeply touched by his philosophical view of
life and death," some 100 medical college students said after
signing up to donate.
</P>
<P>
About 4000 people have registered at Tongren Eye Bank since it
was established by Tongren Hospital in 1990, a staff member said.
</P>
<P>
However, Tongren and many other Chinese hospitals are short of
eyes and organs for transplants due to people's traditional view
that the remains of the deceased should not be dissected.
</P>
<P>
"Lots of patients become handicapped or even die because they
can't get organs for transplants in time. Many hospitals and
medical institutes can hardly carry out research on difficult
illness cases due to shortage of patients' remains," Beijing
Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
"As medics, we should take the lead in adapting customs and
changing traditions," the report quoted Huang Huiming, a doctor at
the Beijing Friendship Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Influenced by Deng's requests to have his remains dissected for
medical research and his ashes scattered into sea, more than 500
people in east China's Nanjing City have joined in an organ
donation group. And 410 Shanghai residents signed up to have their
cremated remains scattered at sea, according to local newspaper
reports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
