<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Chongqing  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The State Council today forwarded
to the fifth session of the Eighth National People's Congress a
motion on the establishment of Chongqing as a provincial-level
municipality directly under the authority of the central
government. Following is a brief introduction to Chongqing:
</P>
<P>
Chongqing is one of China's exceptionally large cities with a
history of more than 3,000 years. It is the largest economic
center, city and an important transportation hub in southwestern
China and on the upper reach of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
As early as in the Shang Dynasty (about 16th-11th century B.C.)
and the period of the Warring States (475 B.C-221 B.C), Chongqing
was capital of the Ba State. It later became Ba Prefecture in the
Qin Dynasty (221 B.C-207 B.C.) and down through the Eastern Han
Dynasty (25-220). In the Sui Dynasty (581-618), Chongqing was made
Yu Prefecture and was later set up as Chongqing Prefecture in the
Song Dynasty (960-1279).
</P>
<P>
In 1891, Chongqing was opened up as a trading port and in 1929
was officially established as a city. After the outbreak of the
War of Resistance against Japan, the Kuomintang government moved
westward to Chongqing and coastal industries were also moved to
the interior. In 1940, Chongqing was made a "wartime capital" by
the Kuomintang government and was the political, economic,
commercial, trade, financial, transportation, cultural and
diplomatic center at that time.
</P>
<P>
In the early years after the founding of the People's Republic
of China, Chongqing was home to the Communist Party of China
Central Committee's Southwestern Bureau and Southwestern Military
and Political Commission, as well as a municipality directly under
the authority of the central government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Chongqing  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1954, Chongqing was changed into a city at the prefectural
level administered by Sichuan Province. The State granted it a
separate power away from the province in making economic
development plans between 1954-1958. In the middle of the 1960s,
Chongqing was a major area for defense industry-related
construction and became an important national industrial base. In
February, 1983, the CPC Central Committee and the State Council
designated Chongqing as one of the first group of cities to
experiment with restructuring of the economic system and as a city
with a separate power away from the province in making economic
development plans and with the status of a province in the
administration of the economy, and it was also opened up as a
foreign trade port.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing lies in the southeastern part of the Sichuan Basin,
measuring 208 km from the east to the west and 220 km from the
south to the north. Urban Chongqing, located in a hilly area where
the Yangtze River and the Jialingjiang River meet, has an area of
23,114 sq km, about four percent of the total area of Sichuan
Province. The city proper has an area of 1,534 sq km. Chongqing
now administers 11 districts and 10 counties and had a population
of 15.2 million at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposal of the State Council, the
administrative areas under Wanxian Municipality, Fuling
Municipality and Qianjiang Prefecture will be incorporated into
Chongqing after it is lifted to the status of a provincial-level
municipality, raising its total area to 82,000 sq km and its
population to 30.2 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Chongqing  (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chongqing has developed rapidly economically and socially since
the third plenum of the 11th CPC Central Committee. Its gross city
product reached 74.3 billion yuan in 1995, a four-fold increase
over 1978. The per capita income for living expenses of urban
residents hit 4,053 yuan and that of farmers 1,554 yuan.
Chongqing's industrial and agricultural output in 1995 reached 144
billion yuan, with 120.1 billion yuan coming from industries. The
city's service sector reported an output of 24.7 billion yuan in
1995, about 33 percent of the local GDP
</P>
<P>
Currently, Chongqing has more than 2.1 million commercial
outlets and nearly 300 financial institutions. It has established
economic and trade relations with 110 countries and regions
throughout the world, with an annual import and export volume of
nearly 1.5 billion US dollars. A total of 1,500 overseas-funded
projects have been approved, with actual overseas investment
valued at 1.7 billion US dollars. The number of overseas-funded
enterprises now stands at 1,575.
</P>
<P>
The Chengdu-Chongqing, Sichuan-Guizhou and Xiangfan-Chongqing
railways meet in Chongqing. The Chengdu-Chongqing expressway for
motor cars has opened to traffic and the Chongqing port's handling
capacity has reached 6.3 million tons. The Chongqing airport has
opened more than 30 domestic routes and direct chartered flights
to Hong Kong and Japan. The newly-built Jiangbei airport can
accommodate Boeing-747 passenger planes.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing enjoys scientific and technological advantages in
West China. Currently, it has 340 scientific research institutions
of various kinds, 33 universities and colleges, and more than
350,000 scientific and technological personnel of all sorts.
</P>
<P>
If the State Council motion is adopted, Chongqing will join
Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai as the fourth provincial-level
municipality directly under the authority of the central
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
