<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Starts Spring Sowing   (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China's major grain producers are
preparing for spring sowing, kicking off the nationwide drive for
another bumper crop after the record-breaking harvest of 1996.
</P>
<P>
South China, which enjoys a warmer climate and more rainfall
than North China, led the nation in seeding rice. Provinces in
Central and Northern China ready themselves for spring ploughing,
a crucial step for high output yields.
</P>
<P>
China is making a sustained effort to attain its ambitious goal
to feed its population of 1.2 billion. It set a historical record
in grain production last year with the national output topping 480
billion kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Despite two promising consecutive harvests, the Central
Government remains prudent, and urged all localities to keep a
tight control on grain production early this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, the area sown to
grain crops in China will cover 1.68 billion mu (about 110 million
ha) this year. Some 60-70 percent of the land will cater to summer
crops. The gross grain output should remain at the 1996 level.
</P>
<P>
In east China's Zhejiang, Fujian, Anhui and Jiangxi provinces,
one of the major grain-producing areas in China, the total acreage
of summer crops stands at three million ha.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi, which sells an average one billion kg of grain to the
state each year, pledged to stabilize the crop fields at 3.5
million ha and increase government allocation for agricultural use
by 20 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
South China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region plans to sow
grain crops on 3.6 million ha of land this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Starts Spring Sowing  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Farm households in Zhejiang and Jiangsu provinces started
tilling the land soon after the Spring Festival, which fell on
February 7. Provincial government of Fujian gave all-round support
for building 30 commodity grain bases, improving low-output fields,
and river harnessing.
</P>
<P>
Data provided by the Ministry of Water Resources showed China
invested 32.2 billion yuan in irrigation projects last winter to
pave way for the spring ploughing.
</P>
<P>
Some provinces have distributed an abundant supply of fertilizer,
improved seed strains and farm chemicals. The price of many raw
materials are roughly same as that of last year, sometimes drifting
lower.
</P>
<P>
The progress of agro-science proved decisive in achieving last
year's record grain harvest. Statistics indicate the ratio of
success of the harvest attributable to scientific technique in China
climbed to 39 percent last year, an increase of five percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
And agricultural experts predict that agro-science will
continue to be a key factor in obtaining a good yield for this
year since the land area for crops can expect only marginal
expansion, and weather remains unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
More than one million farmers will be trained to master modern
techniques such as sparse-planting and seed-spraying methods,
which can raise the per-ha yield by 600 kg and 1,125 kg respectively.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi is to plant hybrid rice on 666,000 ha of land this
year. Fujian will continue to popularize 10 high-yield
agro-techniques. Zhejiang will bring more land under irrigation,
improve 66,000 ha of poor land and build more agricultural
experimental plots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Calls for Restructuring of UN, Regional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting South African President
Nelson Mandela today called for "rapid restructuring" of the
United Nations and for vigorous pursuit of the concept of the
Indian Ocean Rim in the process of establishing new world order.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his speech here, entitled "South and Southern Africa
into the Next Century" at the 16th Singapore Lecture, Mandela said
that the first challenge nations throughout the world now face is
the restructuring of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"There is no gainsaying that no other body can give leadership
to the evolution of the new world order than the UN," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We in South Africa, along with the Organization of African
Unity and the Non-Aligned Movement are calling for a rapid
restructuring of this world body to ensure that continents and
regions of the world can play an effective role in the
restructuring of international relations," Mandela stressed.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure the pooling of sovereignty rather than the
submergence of other nations by the most powerful, the UN must be
accorded its central place in the conduct of world affairs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The second challenge pertains to regional integration, Mandela
said, noting that among developing countries, much progress has
been made in consolidating such regional blocs as the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and the Southern Africa
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
The concept of the Indian Ocean Rim should be pursued with
vigor, as the idea starts to address this challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
The South African President also called for efforts to
"rekindle old relationships" between Africa and Asia, saying, "We
yearn to rebuild what was destroyed. We seek to forge strong
multilateral ties among our nations under the new and more
favorable conditions of freedom, technological advance and peace."
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who turns 79 in July, arrived here on Wednesday on his
first state visit to Singapore. He met with Singapore President
Ong Teng Cheong and other senior officials after his arrival and
would meet Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong before winding up the
visit later today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
