<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build Fast Neutron Experimental Reactor Power Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China plans to complete its first
fast neutron reactor power plant by the end of the century, in
order to meet its increasing energy needs.
</P>
<P>
The experimental fast reactor power plant, which will be built
at a total cost of 860 million yuan (about 103 million US
dollars), will be the largest high-tech energy project contained
in the state's "863" high-tech development program.
</P>
<P>
The reactor, believed to be more efficient and safer and with a
higher utilization rate of uranium, will develop a thermal power
of 65 MWt and an electrical power of 20 MWe, providing the
technical basis for the country's first commercial fast reactor
power plant at the beginning of the next century.
</P>
<P>
"To build a fast reactor power plant is of vital significance
for China's energy development in the next century," said Yang
Tianlu, vice-president of the China Institute of Atomic Energy and
general director of China's fast reactor project.
</P>
<P>
He said that it will sharply raise the utilization rate of the
rare nuclear fuel -- uranium, from around one percent by the
existing pressurized water reactors to 60 or 70 percent in the new
fast reactors.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu Mi, chief engineer of China's Fast Reactor
Research Center, the operational Chinese Daya Bay and Qinshan
nuclear power plants, both equipped with pressurized water
reactors, will continue to play an important role in meeting the
country's energy needs.
</P>
<P>
However, the senior expert expressed the view that large-scale
development of pressurized water reactors would be difficult in
China because of the country's limited uranium reserves.
</P>
<P>
Xu revealed that the feasibility study for the experimental
fast reactor has been approved by the government and the relevant
departments. And the basic design, site choice, environmental
protection, and construction blueprints have all passed examination.
</P>
<P>
According to schedule, the earthwork of the project will start
this October. Concrete will be pored in May 1998, and construction
will be completed by 2000. The fast reactor power plant will start
generating electricity for the power grid by 2003.
</P>
<P>
China's energy needs will be equivalent to one billion tons
of standard coal by the middle of the next century, according to a
research report on China's Energy Needs by 2050, which was jointly
produced by the China State Science and Technology Commission
and the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
To narrow the widening gap between energy demand and supply,
China has to boost nuclear power development in the next century,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate China will develop a nuclear power capacity of
40 million kw by the year 2020, or six percent of the country's
electricity generating capacity, as compared to the existing one
percent.
</P>
<P>
By 2050, the country's total installed nuclear power capacity
will grow to 240 million kw, 20 percent of the country's projected
generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
There are now eight operational fast reactor power plants
worldwide. The first one was built in the United States in
1946. China started research in fast reactor power plants in
1965. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
