<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Doctors Call Off Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan doctors of the
Government Medical Officers Association (GMOA) who commenced a 24
hour strike Wednesday called it off soon after the government
appointed a ministerial committee to examine their demands,
official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the doctors staged a four-hour token strike over
salary anomalies demanding the restoration of their on-call and
availability allowance of Rs 2,000 (35 US dollars) per month and
the payment of the new academic allowance to doctors engaged in
teaching undergraduates, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's protest strike which was a follow-up of the token
strike was called off as soon as the government intimated its
decision to appoint the Ministerial Committee to study the salary
anomaly dispute as the GMOA intended to create an atmosphere
conducive to a dispassionate study of the dispute, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Following the commencement of the strike Wednesday, many
patients who turned up at hospitals returned home disappointed and
dejected. They had hoped that the hospitals would function
following President Chandrika Kumaratunga's call to the GMOA to
act with responsibility and refrain from any course of action that
would imperil the lives of poor patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
