<HEADLINE> Air India Scraps Some International Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Air India has discontinued its
flights to Canada, Australia and South Africa following Civil
Aviation Minister C.M. Ibrahim's advice to pull out of
commercially unviable routes, the Hindustan Times said today.
</P>
<P>
Besides, frequency on several destinations in Europe, including
Paris and Frankfurt, has also been reduced to cut losses.
</P>
<P>
Pulling out flights from these destinations was part of a new
route management strategy which is being implemented to make
operations commercially viable and profitable, Air India sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Stating that the company would now follow a dynamic routing
policy in line with seasonal fluctuations, they confirmed that the
Bombay-Delhi-Toronto, Bombay-Sydney-Perth and the
Bombay-Johannesburg-Durban flights have been scrapped for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
Some of the aircraft freed from these routes have been pressed
in new flights launched on the profitable routes linking India
with some Gulf countries and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The airline is likely to launch a flight to Spain in May or
June when the tourist inflow from that country to India increases.
</P>
<P>
The other destinations which are being discussed now include
Seoul and Brunei.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
