<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Impose Value Added Tax This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is
determined to introduce a Value Added Tax (VAT) regime to increase
the national revenue this year despite strong opposition from the
business community, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Finance Ministry's VAT department said they
are busy in making all necessary preparations for the
implementation of the new tax as the government decided to impose
it from the coming 1997-98 fiscal year starting in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The department will begin to list the names of all businessmen
who come under the VAT tax net next month, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, businessmen here vehemently criticized the
government's decision on the new tax regime, saying that the time
is not ripe yet for the country to implement the VAT, which is
expected to replace various existing taxes including excise and
sales tax.
</P>
<P>
Hasty introduction of such a new regime without adequate
homework could put the whole taxation system into disorder, they
said.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Nepalese Chamber of Commerce and Industry
(FNCCI) and the Nepal Chamber of Commerce (NCC), the country's two
leading business organizations, have urged the government to
improve the management of current taxation system instead of
imposing the TAX immediately.
</P>
<P>
But tax officials said there is no alternative to the VAT if
the government wants to counter the rampant tax evasion activities
in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to a VAT Department official, the government will
nearly double its annual tax revenue to around 200 million US
dollars under the new VAT system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
