<HEADLINE> Thai Ailing Finance Firms Face Heavy Withdrawals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Depositors continued to withdraw
money from finance firms on Wednesday after the central bank
announced that 10 local finance firms faced serious financial
problems, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawals from all finance companies in Thailand topped
12 billion baht (480 million U.S. dollars) on Wednesday, bringing
the total over the past two days to 21.4 billion baht (840 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 10 firms alone saw withdrawals of 6 billion baht (240
million dollars) on Wednesday. The total withdrawals from the 10
firms over the past two days amounted to 10 billion baht (400
million dollars), accounting for 15.16 percent of their combined
deposits.
</P>
<P>
Depositors were requiring the government to step in to help the
ailing sector.
</P>
<P>
Although withdrawals on Wednesday were more than Tuesday, the
central bank still expressed confidence that the situation would
return to normal very soon.
</P>
<P>
The authorities on Monday published a list of 10 finance firms
which were in financial trouble through excessive expansion and
involvement on the property market.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand suspended the share trading in
the banking and financial sectors on the day, which triggered an
upset in the country.
</P>
<P>
The government has introduced a rescue package to ease the
situation, including merger programs and requirements for the 10
firms to increase their reserves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
