<HEADLINE> South China City to Improve Foreign Investment Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Industrial projects, not real
estate, has now become the most attractive bet for overseas
investors in the capital city of southernmost China's Hainan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Haikou has made a concerted effort to attract overseas
investors to fund new and traditional sectors of local industry.
</P>
<P>
Last year nearly 84 percent of output value generated by local
foreign-funded enterprises, or nearly 1.5 billion yuan, stemmed
from industrial production.
</P>
<P>
And more than 33 percent of profits earned by the city's
foreign-funded enterprises, or more than 30 million yuan, also
came from industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
Inflow of overseas investment gives an impetus to local
economic development, with foreign-funded enterprises contributing
to more than 18 percent of the city's GDP in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year also saw overseas-funded enterprises generate more
than 23 percent of the city's industrial output value, and conduct
nearly 21 percent of local export. 
</P>
