<HEADLINE> Swedish Minister: No Hurry to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Swedish Defense Minister
Bjorn Von Sydow said today that his country was not in a hurry to
join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Before heading home after his one-day visit here, Sydow said
Sweden would follow the non-alliance policy under the five-year
defense plan approved by the parliament last December.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish government believed, the defense chief noted, that
there was nothing at present to press for changes in the country's
position on the defense matter.
</P>
<P>
Sweden would work closely with NATO under the Peace for
Partnership program, in ways such as its participation of the
NATO-led peace-keeping operations in Bosnia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the U.S.-Russia summit scheduled to take place
here on March 20, Sydow said he took the event as a serious
dialogue with Russia on NATO's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
There was no sign worth worrying that the leaders of the two
big powers would redefine their territories of influence in Europe
while ignoring opinions made clear by other countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to making the remarks before the press at the Helsinki
airport, the Swedish minister was briefed by his Finnish
counterpart Anneli Taina about the host nation's defense forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
