<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Colombia to Resume Anti-drug Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States today urged
Colombia to resume its aerial spraying of illicit drug crops as
soon as possible and hoped that the suspension was not a policy
change.
</P>
<P>
Colombia quietly suspended spraying operations today in the
wake of a U.S. announcement that Colombia was among the countries
which were decertified as U.S. allies in the war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters
today that the government made the decision when its estimates
showed a 32 percent increase in the cultivation of coca in
Colombia, making it the second largest grower in the world.
</P>
<P>
Burns said that the United States has not received any
explanation for the decision to suspend the spraying, but "We hope
that this decision has been taken for technical reasons only and
not policy reasons."
</P>
<P>
He added, "We certainly urge a resumption of eradication
operations as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
Joaquin Polo, head of the Colombian National Drug Policy
office, said that spraying had been temporarily suspended until
the government reviewed all its anti-drug agreements with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Washington last Friday decertified Colombia for the second
year running as an ally in the drug war.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian government said that it rejected the U.S.
"unilateral and partial evaluation mechanisms in the fight against
drug trafficking." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
