<HEADLINE> Senior Figure Quits Former Mongolian Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Tserenpiliin Gombosuren, an
active political figure of the Mongolian People's Revolutionary
Party (MPRP), announced on Tuesday he was quitting the party, the
local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
As minister of external relations from June, 1988 to July,
1996, Gombosuren won high praise within the country and around the
world for his bold reform of Mongolia's foreign policy. He became
a member of the MPRP leading committee.
</P>
<P>
Gombosuren said in a statement that he withdrew from the former
ruling party because the MPRP failed to fulfill the internal
reform undertakings set before its 22nd Convention, from last
February 21 to 24.
</P>
<P>
At the Convention, the MPRP did not learn a lesson from its
failure in last year's parliamentary election, and did not analyze
it correctly, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gombosuren, who was initially acknowledged by some public
opinion as a competitive candidate to run for the presidency this
year, was eventually not listed among candidates.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said several other parties were deliberating on
nominating Gombosuren as their presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
However, Gombosuren noted that his decision to quit had nothing
to do with the forthcoming presidential election, and he had no
intention of joining other parties in the future.
</P>
<P>
Gombosuren is still chairman of the board of a joint venture
securities company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
