<HEADLINE> Colombia, Belize Reject U.S. Evaluation on Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Colombia and Belize told the
Organization of American States (OAS) today that they reject the
United States "unilateral evaluation mechanisms" in the fight
against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Colombian ambassador to the OAS, Carlos Holmes Trujillo,
told a meeting of the Permanent Council of the OAS that "Colombia
has reject and continues to reject, in principle, unilateral and
partial evaluation mechanisms in the fight against drug
trafficking."
</P>
<P>
He said, "It rejects them because regional and multilateral
strategies and United Nations agencies are in place to evaluate
the fight against drugs, free of political or economic interests
and based on objective criteria."
</P>
<P>
Trujillo added that his government rejects such mechanisms
which often pull relations between two countries into
confrontation instead of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government announced last Friday its decision
decertifying a number of countries, including Colombia and Belize,
as its allies in the war against drugs.
</P>
<P>
The permanent representative of Belize to the OAS, Ambassador
James Murphy, also read a statement issued by Belizean foreign
minister Dean Barrow Tuesday, expressing "dismay" at allegations
his country had not cooperated in the fight against dug
trafficking.
</P>
<P>
"The government utterly rejects those allegations," the
Caribbean diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Belize remains committed to the fight
against illegal drugs and international crime, and will
cooperate fully with all legitimate regional and international
efforts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
But the Belizean foreign minister said that his government would
not be coerced into signing treaties with clauses that violate
Belize's Constitution and laws.
</P>
<P>
"The Belizean government counts on the full support of the
Belizean people for this stand in defense of Belizean sovereignty
and rights," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
