<HEADLINE> Iraq Calls for Lifting of U.N. Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today called for the United
Nations Security Council to lift the sanctions applied to Iraq
since the end of the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow press reported that Iraq Deputy Prime Minister and
Foreign Minister, Tarik Aziz, made the call during a working visit
to Moscow. He said it was time for the U.N. to consider lifting
the sanctions as the country had fulfilled its obligations in
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Aziz criticized the United States and Britain for preventing
the U.N. from lifting the ban, at a joint news briefing given by
him and Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
Aziz claimed that the two countries' real purpose was to
"isolate and weaken Iraq," in order to "seek gains and maintain
their hegemony in the Gulf region."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official praised Russia's "friendly, just and proper
stand" towards his country.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said he hoped all restrictions on Iraq's oil exports
would be eliminated this year.
</P>
<P>
The Russian minister told reporters that a delegation from the
Energy Ministry would be sent to Iraq to prepare for trade
exchanges between the two countries after the ban was lifted.
</P>
<P>
Aziz arrived in Moscow on Tuesday for a working visit. 
</P>
