<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laos Plans to Propose New Border Pass with Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Laos is planning to propose a new
border pass that will enable Thais and Laotians to cross the
border freely, according to a report reaching here today from
Vientiane.
</P>
<P>
Soutsakhone Pattammavong, director-general of consular affairs
of the Lao Foreign Ministry, was quoted as saying that the
proposal calls for a border pass holder to be given a two-week
visa to travel anywhere in Thailand or Laos.
</P>
<P>
This would cover all of Thailand's 76 provinces and Laos' 16.
Currently, pass holders can only travel within 25 kilometers of
their point of entry.
</P>
<P>
Laos plans to submit a draft proposal to Thailand for
consideration before the two countries meet on the subject, and
the meeting is expected to take place in Vientiane later this
month.
</P>
<P>
A similar proposal will be put to Laos' other neighbors --
Vietnam, China, Cambodia and Myanmar -- if the deal with Thailand
is successful, Soutsakhone said.
</P>
<P>
Soutsakhone said Laos will propose freer movement for
businessmen, including a multiple entry visa for border pass
holders, and equal treatment for passport holders.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Laos grants Thai businessmen multiple-entry visas
valid for six months, while Thailand only allows Laotian
businessmen double entry over a period of three months.
</P>
<P>
"The Thai side claims it's a matter of immigration
regulations," Soutsakhone said
</P>
<P>
He said he would ask Thailand to relax regulations on Laotian
visitors.
</P>
<P>
At present, Laotians who want to visit Thailand must produce a
bank statement showing they have at least 10,000 baht (about 400
US dollars) in their account to guarantee their return.
</P>
<P>
Soutsakhone said this is unrealistic because most Laotians are
poor and have no bank savings, and are thus discouraged from
traveling to Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
