<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upper House Adopts Law on World War II Art Trophy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Federation Council, the
upper house of parliament, today passed a law on World War II art
trophy despite the government's opposition.
</P>
<P>
The legislation declares that art objects moved by the former
Soviet Union to the territory of Russia during and after World War
II belong to Russia's national property.
</P>
<P>
An Itar-Tass news agency report said the law was unanimously
approved with 140 votes.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Tuesday, the Russian government said
Russia's unilateral claim of ownership of the relocated art
objects is against international accords and international law.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the new law, the government noted, will
lead to serious political consequences as it fails to divide the
art objects along the line of aggressors and the aggressed.
</P>
<P>
Already passed by the Duma, or the lower house of parliament,
and pending the signature by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, the
law has caused strong repercussions from Europeans countries.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to President Yeltsin, Dutch Prime Minister Wim Kok
asked him to help return the art objects belonging to the
Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
