<HEADLINE> Draft Law on Election of HK Deputies Submitted for NPC Deliberation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-six deputies to the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), the Chinese legislature, from
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) will be elected
before the end of January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
This represents an increase of eight deputies over the current
number of Hong Kong deputies to the NPC, according to a draft
method on the election of deputies from the Hong Kong SAR to the
Ninth NPC. The draft method was submitted to the Fifth Session of
the Eighth NPC here today for deliberation.
</P>
<P>
Cao Zhi, secretary-general of the NPC Standing Committee, made
explanations on the draft at the session.
</P>
<P>
According to a draft allocation plan for deputies to be elected
to the Ninth NPC, which is under deliberation by the NPC general
session, one deputy is to be elected from about every 220,000
urban residents and from about every 880,000 rural residents.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong had a population of 6.31 million (all calculated as
city residents) in 1995, and in accordance with the draft plan,
the SAR should have 29 deputies to the Ninth NPC (it has 28
deputies to the Eighth NPC).
</P>
<P>
Given the special status of the SAR, Cao said, an extra seven
is added, making the total number of deputies 36.
</P>
<P>
The draft method stipulates the establishment of a deputies
election conference in the Hong Kong SAR, which will elect the
SAR's deputies to the Ninth NPC under the direction of the NPC
Standing Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
