<HEADLINE> Philippine Agrarian Reform Plan Gets ADB Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has committed to extend a 50 million US dollar loan to support the
Philippines' agrarian reform program, officials from the
Manila-based bank said today.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to support the development of 75 to 100
agrarian reform communities in the country, preferably those that
have not received any support from other foreign agencies.
</P>
<P>
The agrarian reform communities are among the most
disadvantaged communities in the Philippines, lacking adequate
physical and social infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
It is for this reason the World Bank extended a 50 million US
dollar loan to the agrarian reform communities, while Japan's
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund gave another 50 million US
dollars for the development of these communities.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a preparatory technical assistance grant of
250,000 US dollars was extended by the ADB to the project.
</P>
<P>
The ADB also dispatched a fact-finding mission early this year
to some communities in several provinces to look into whether
local government units have the funds and can carry out projects
and maintain physical infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's social reform agenda, the agrarian reform
communities were designated as conduits for agricultural
development, basic infrastructure development and
productivity-enhancing efforts.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Department of Agrarian Reform has identified 862
agrarian reform communities nationwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
