<HEADLINE> World Bank to Grant Loans to Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is expected to grant
Bulgaria loans totaling 260 million to 290 million U.S. dollars
over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the government's press center disclosed this
after a meeting between Stefan Sofiianski, the Bulgarian Prime
Minister, and Marselo Selovski, the special representative of the
vice chief executive of the World Bank, Mari Elen Briknel earlier
today.
</P>
<P>
During Selovski's visit, he elaborated on the World Bank's loan
plan for Bulgaria for 1997, which aimed at helping it solve
financial difficulties in importing grain and medicine, and in
economic reform, the spokesman said..
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the bank will grant four million U.S. dollars
in loans to Bulgaria next month in a bid to help it import
medicine, grain and food on condition that Bulgaria ensured the
deregulation of grain and food.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bank would provide 50 to 80 million U.S.
dollars in social relief funds and 170 million U.S. dollars for
Bulgarian economic reform this year. 
