<HEADLINE> Deputies to China's Ninth NPC to be Elected Before January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A draft decision on the number and
election of deputies to the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC)
was submitted to the fifth session of the Eighth NPC for
examination.
</P>
<P>
According to the draft, which is based on the Constitution and
the Election Law, nearly 3,000 deputies to the Ninth NPC will have
been elected throughout the country before the end of next
January.
</P>
<P>
The total number of deputies to the Ninth NPC will not exceed
3,000, the draft says. It also says that one deputy will be
elected out of every 880,000 people in the countryside and out of
every 220,000 people in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Also according to the draft decision:
</P>
<P>
In the provinces and autonomous regions with a very small
population, the number of deputies from each should be no fewer
than 15;
</P>
<P>
Taiwan province will temporarily elect 13 deputies from people
of Taiwan-origin in the provinces, autonomous regions,
centrally-administered municipalities and the People's Liberation
Army (PLA), and the remaining deputy quota Taiwan is entitled to
in accordance with law will be retained;
</P>
<P>
The PLA will elect 265 deputies;
</P>
<P>
Ethnic minorities account for around 12 percent of the total
number of NPC deputies, and for ethnic groups with a particularly
small population, there should be at least one NPC deputy for
each;
</P>
<P>
Of all deputies, 35 should be elected out of returned overseas
Chinese;
</P>
<P>
The proportion of female deputies should be bigger than that of
the Eighth NPC;
</P>
<P>
To ensure that a proper proportion of deputies is elected out
of areas and ethnic groups with a particularly small population
and out of areas with a concentration of people of various
circles, a certain quota out of the total number of deputies will
be allocated to relevant provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities by the NPC Standing Committee for election; and
</P>
<P>
A method for the election of deputies from the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region will be decided separately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
