<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More People in China's Poorest Area Escape Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Well over 500,000 people in
Xihaigu Prefecture, one of the poorest areas in China, escaped
poverty this year thanks to relief efforts by the Central
Government.
</P>
<P>
The two million people in the eight county prefecture in the
southern part of China's Ningxia Hui (muslim) Autonomous Region,
have suffered from soil erosion, hail, frost, flood, windstorms,
and recently a long-lasting drought.
</P>
<P>
Since 1983, the Central Government has allocated tens of
millions of yuan each year to develop the local economy of the
30,456 sq km region.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics, grain output of Xihaigu
soared to 755 million kg last year, up 90.2 percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 average grain and per capital income of residents in
Guyuan, the poorest area, increased by 90.8 percent and 52.2
percent, respectively, compared to the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Local government officials attribute the progress to farmland
improvement and spread of agro-techniques.
</P>
<P>
The region has improved 14,333 ha of farmland, dug 43,000 water
wells, covered 17,200 ha of maize field with plastic film in a bid
to raise output. And 1,128 short-term technical courses trained
100,000 young farmers in new techniques.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the region has built six pillar industries based on
local-made beef, amylum, fruit, herbal medicine, building material
and flax.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Call off Settlement Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- In a formal United Nations
Security Council meeting on Wednesday, Israel was urged strongly
by member states to call off its plan to build Jewish settlements
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 countries were enlisted as speakers at the
meeting on Israel's plan to build 6,500 homes in East
Jerusalem. The meeting is scheduled to run into Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Calling it "a new colonial settlement", the Permanent Observer
of Palestine to the United Nations, Nasser Al-Kidwa, described the
housing project as was one of a series of Israeli measures and
actions over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
These measures, he said, "constitute a clear policy aimed at
the continuation of the Judization of the city of Jerusalem,
changing its legal status and its demographic composition."
</P>
<P>
He called upon the international community to protect and
uphold its will reflected in various U.N. resolutions, to restrain
Israel from continuing to ignore this will and from its persistent
violation of International Law.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the council meeting, Chinese Permanent
Representative to the United Nation, Qin Huasun, urged Israel to
stop its plan to build the settlements.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the view that is bound to set serious obstacles to
the Palestine-Israel peace process and will be detrimental to the
Middle East peace process as a whole," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The question of Jerusalem should be settled by the parties
concerned through negotiations on the basis of the relevant U.N.
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Any unilateral move contrary to this approach should be
avoided, since it will only further complicate the question
instead of rendering any help to its proper settlement, or to the
Middle East peace process."
</P>
<P>
Sergey V. Lavrov, permanent representative for Russia, said
Russia shared the negative response of the Palestinians, Arab and
Islamic States, and the international community to this
"inconsiderate and untimely step" taken by Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said the Israeli decision clouded the negotiating
environment in the Middle East, especially at the threshold of the
start in mid-March of talks on the final status.
</P>
<P>
"A co-sponsor of the peace process, Russia is convinced that the
situation requires action so as to avoid relapses to tensions in
Palestinian-Israeli relations similar to the events of last
September," he said.
</P>
<P>
United States Ambassador Bill Richardson said the U.S. "is
concerned by the decision announced by the Israeli government."
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe such activity is helpful to the peace
process," he said. "We believe that this decision undermines the
trust and confidence that is so badly needed if a lasting peace is
to be achieved." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
