<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Condemns Kidnapping of Journalists in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister
Vitaly Ignatenko today condemned the kidnapping of journalists in
Chechnya as an act of political provocation against the new
leadership of the Chechen republic.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after addressing the State Duma,
Ignatenko said the Russian government would establish direct
contact with the leadership of Chechnya in order to settle the
issue.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported earlier in the day that four
Russian journalists were abducted Tuesday by unidentified gunmen
in Chechnya when they were heading home to the outskirts of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
The Chechen Interior Ministry confirmed the abductions, but
give no further information.
</P>
<P>
A Chechen, who acted as their driver and bodyguard, was not
taken and alerted the police.
</P>
<P>
The kidnapped victims are identified as Nikolai Zagnoiko of
Itar-Tass, Yuri Arkhipov, Nikolai Mamulashvili and Lev Zeltser of
government-run Radio Russia.
</P>
<P>
The captors, believed to be criminal gangs seeking ransom
money, fired shots at the car and took the newsmen away in another
car.
</P>
<P>
It was not the first time that journalists were kidnapped in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
In January, two Russian television reporters were kidnapped and
held captive for a month before being released. Ten days ago, an
Italian photographer working for the Mandatori publishing house
was abducted in downtown Grozny while covering an official rally.
</P>
<P>
The increasing of abduction of journalists was becoming an
"international issue," the Russian deputy prime minister said,
adding that it is quite possible to solve the problem with the
participation of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe and other international organizations.
</P>
<P>
Also today, the Russian Journalist Union (RJU) condemned the
event and described the situation in Chechnya as "violence of
raging crime."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the RJU called on all mass media not to send any
reporters to the Caucasus republic.
</P>
<P>
Kidnapping, usually for ransom money, is widespread in the
mountainous region which ended its 21-month armed conflict with
Moscow last August.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all men in the largely destroyed region are armed.
Russian journalists, foreign aid workers and ordinary citizens are
all targets of kidnappers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
