<HEADLINE> Japanese Aid to Bangladesh May Drop Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 6 (Xinhua) --A Japanese economic team on Wednesday
said the donor country would extend all possible cooperation to
Bangladesh, but hinted that future assistance could drop
significantly, said official sources.
</P>
<P>
The indication came from the Japanese mission that has been
attending a two-day consultation which began here on Wednesday to
discuss new development projects to be implemented with Japanese
loans.
</P>
<P>
The annual meeting is being held after a two-year interval and
Bangladesh is likely to seek 610 million US dollars for eight
development projects, mainly in infrastructure and power sector,
from Tokyo in today's crucial meeting.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the Japanese team suggested that
Bangladesh concentrate more on "self-help efforts" for its
development endeavors, but said Japan would continue to consider
the case of Bangladesh as exceptional one.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting on Wednesday, the two sides discussed the
general issues of economic policy and the progress of projects
being implemented with soft loan from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Japan is one of the largest bilateral donors for Bangladesh,
offering on an average 200 million dollars annually to this
undeveloped country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
