<HEADLINE> Macedonian Army Placed on Alert Against Unrest in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Macedonian troops have been on high
alert in response to the worsening situation in Albania, said a
report from the Macedonian Information Center today.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia, with a large number of ethnic Albanians in the
population along its border with Albania, has beefed up security
around its military facilities and increased patrols along the
border areas.
</P>
<P>
The measures, taken since a state of emergency was imposed in
Albania on Sunday, aim to prevent armed conflicts and refugee
inflows as the tension was escalated in the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
Macedonian Prime Minister Branko Cruenkovsik has called again
for a longer stay of the United Nations Preventive Deployment
Force in the former republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N. resolution, the mandate for the U.N. force in
Macedonia will expire on May 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
The anti-government insurgence in Albania was initiated by the
collapse of five once popular get-rich-quick investment schemes,
in which most Albanian families lost money.
</P>
<P>
Some angry protesters have turned violent, and have stormed
police, seized an array of weapons from state arsenals, and then
gone on a rampage of looting and burning.
</P>
<P>
European nations have expressed grave concerns over the
situation in Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
