<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Ban Unskilled Workers Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will no longer send
unskilled workers overseas, especially maids, from April next
year, according to official sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Wednesday at a cabinet meeting chaired by
President Soeharto, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The meeting concluded that there is a high overseas demand for
skilled Indonesian workers in various fields such as shipping, air
transport, hospital and paramedical services, construction,
electronics, industry and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Official data showed that out of almost one million Indonesians
working overseas last year, 38 percent were unskilled.
</P>
<P>
In the terms of money, the Indonesian workers abroad sent home
approximately 4.8 billion US dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
This year, the government expected to send some 1.2 million
workers overseas, who will receive an estimated combined total of
5.8 billion dollars for the year, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The figure is expected to double to 2.5 million overseas
workers around the year 2000, receiving a combined yearly income
of 12.5 billion dollars, Manpower Minister Abdul Latief said
earlier.
</P>
<P>
These earnings are expected to rise further to 18.8 billion
dollars in 2003, the minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
