<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Seeks to Reform Banking System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Cuba is planning to restructure its
banking system to give the island access to international
financial markets, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
At the fourth round-table meeting organized by the Cuban
government and the British publication "The Economist", Cuba's
National Bank President Francisco Soberon said reform included
institutional changes, technological modernization and the
re-training of personnel.
</P>
<P>
Cuba wanted to avoid the experience of former socialist
countries that created small private banks and financial
institutions, which were interested in short-term profits,
Francisco Soberon said.
</P>
<P>
According to the reform plan, Cuba will create a banking system
with seven banks under the strict supervision of a central
entity. The central body will incorporate 13 representative
offices of foreign financial institutions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The president said they would keep in close contact with
creditors of the island in order to normalize external financial
relations without taking on commitments, which would limit the
government's capacity to decide on how to manage the economy.
</P>
<P>
New medium and long-term loan transactions would be formalized
with several countries and Cuba was continuing its talks with
those countries, Soberon added.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the banking and financial institutions operating in
the country granted about 440 million U.S dollars worth of loans
to Cuban entrepreneurs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0278 </DOCNO>
