<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Investment Panel Sets New Rules for Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors who want to
obtain residence permits in Thailand will be required to buy
either government bonds or condominium units worth at least eight
million baht (about 320,000 US dollars), the Board of Investment
(BOI) of Thailand decided Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Their spouses and children will also be required to invest at
least six million baht (about 240,000 US dollars) and two million
baht (80,000 us dollars) respectively in bonds or condominium
units.
</P>
<P>
The requirement is subject to cabinet approval.
</P>
<P>
The government bonds to be sold to foreigners would have a
maturity of five years. Ownership of the bonds would be
transferable, or they would be mortgaged if the BOI approves.
</P>
<P>
Condominium units cannot be mortgaged, sold or transferred for
at least five years. Developers who want to sell condominium to
foreign investors must register them with the BOI.
</P>
<P>
BOI Secretary-General Staporn Kavitanon was quoted today by
local press as saying that the requirement was designed not only
to attract more foreign investment but also to shore up the
sluggish property business.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
