<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Family Planning Saves 20 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to the successful family
planning in Indonesia, the government managed to save up to 20
billion US dollars in foreign exchange per year, an official said.
</P>
<P>
Assistant to the State Minister for Population Affairs Dr.
Djaelani said Wednesday in Bali island that Indonesia's total
population reached 200 million till early February 1997. A 1970
forecast put the total at 220 million this year, reports reaching
here today said.
</P>
<P>
The smaller total, he said, was achieved thanks to the
successful family planning.
</P>
<P>
If Indonesia's per capita income amounted to 1000 US dollars
per annum, the government could have saved 20 billion dollars, he
said, adding that the population growth rate has been reduced from
2.32 percent in 1970 to only 1.9 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate will drop to 1.2 percent between 2000-2005, and
0.6 percent in 2020-2025, government officials predicted.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show Indonesia's birth rate dropped to 1.7
percent in 1996 and the government is seeking a further reduction
to 1.5 percent by this year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's population control policy was launched in 1970 with
the establishment of the National Family Planning Board, which in
1989 won Indonesia the United Nations' population award.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
