<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third Confucian Family Temple Found In East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A group of buildings first put up
in the Song Dynasty (960-1279) in the central part of east China's
Zhejiang province have been identified as the third Confucian
family temple.
</P>
<P>
Previously, historians believed that China had only two
Confucian family temples, one in Qufu in east China's Shandong
province, the birth place of Confucius, and the other in Quzhou in
the western part of Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
But the Confucian family tree implied the existence of a third
family temple, in "Wuzhou", which, after detailed study by Chinese
scholars, turned out to be in present-day Juxi village, Panan
county, in Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
The scholars have found that the villagers, most of whom have
the family name Kong (the same as Confucius, who is referred to in
Chinese as Kong Fuzi), revere a group of ancient buildings which
they call the "Confucian Family Temple".
</P>
<P>
The temple began in 1255, with its existing buildings mainly
from the Qing Dynasty, built symmetrically along an axis and
facing north.
</P>
<P>
Carved hallways connect a front hall and a back hall in which
were hung the pictures of several generations of family members.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the scale, structure and direction of the
buildings are the strongest evidence that the site is a Confucian
family temple. Moreover, they identified Kong Baoquan, director of
the county People's Congress, who is from Juxi village, as a
descendent of Confucius, from the 74th generation. One of his
ancestors, Kong Duangong, a member of the 48th generation, moved
from Qufu, in Shandong, to Juxi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province To Invest Heavily in Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei Province
plans to put 18 billion yuan into building a combined floor space
of 24.5 million sq m of flats this year as part of its housing
system reform in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Eleven cities directly under the provincial government will
implement "comfortable living" projects to provide standard flats
for moderate to low-income families and will build 1.5 million sq
m of flats.
</P>
<P>
This northern Chinese province led the nation in selling
government-subsidized flats to individuals, and this year, they
are expected to make up 80 percent of the total flats still
waiting to be sold.
</P>
<P>
As early as the beginning of the 1980s, Tangshan City, which
was almost leveled by a severe earthquake in 1976, was chosen by
the State Council as a pilot in the sale of government-subsidized
flats to individuals for large-scale reconstruction, and was
helpful in providing experience for preparing to spread the work
in Hebei and in the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Previously, housing mainly was welfare-oriented
government-owned flats alloted to individuals, with the monthly
rent per sq m kept very low.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the province has sold 77 million sq
m of government-subsidized housing, accounting for more than a
half of the government-subsidized housing authorized for sale.
</P>
<P>
The goal of providing comfortable living space has been reached
earlier than for people outside Hebei, with per capita living
space for urban residents now ten sq m.
</P>
<P>
The province has 421 companies involved in real estate
development, and has seen rapid development in the building
materials sector, of which the province has become a leading
producer.
</P>
<P>
Local sources say that the province is preparing to establish a
new housing bank, whose purpose will be to provide better service
for housing construction.
</P>
<P>
The province has also been revising regulations and rules to
standardize housing construction, marketing, and management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
