<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camera Industry Rebounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China's camera industry witnessed
a rebound last year thanks to effective measures taken by the
authorities to invigorate the sector.
</P>
<P>
The industry's output increased by 35 percent from its 1995
level to surpass 45 million cameras in 1996, with pre-tax profit
rising by 80 percent. said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
China exported about 40 million cameras last year.
</P>
<P>
The country has 28 camera firms, almost all of which are
cooperating with foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Smuggled cameras used to flood China's market.
</P>
<P>
To help solve the problems caused by smuggled cameras, the
authorities issued regulations.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on imported cameras were reduced to 30 percent last
year from 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Authorities also encouraged foreign manufacturers to invest in
China instead of just exporting their products to China.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, five joint ventures were set up with Japan-based
camera manufacturers including Olympus, Minolta, Nikon and Ricoh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the eight domestic enterprises that survived the
rampant smuggling are now able to turn out a total of more than
five million cameras annually and make handsome profits.
</P>
<P>
China's domestic cameras market demand is estimated to be about
nine million in 1997 and is expected to grow in tandem with the
upgrading of people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
Currently, only 39 percent of urban households and a mere one
percent of rural ones in China have cameras.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
