<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Increasing Post and Telecom Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The increase in farmers' incomes
has given a push to post and telecommunications development in
Sichuan, China's most populous province, where rural areas
consider the sector a new pillar for the local economy.
</P>
<P>
Luxian county, in southern Sichuan, for example, which is
located on the upper reaches of the Yangtze river, used to be a
backward region, but increasing demand from farmers for better
post and telecom services has helped the market prosper.
</P>
<P>
The local post and telecom bureau last year had revenues of
10.8 million yuan from the rural telephone business, while 200
million yuan in postal savings deposits brought a profit of 4.6
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local officials attribute the change to farmers' improved
lives. In recent years, farmers who sought temporary work
eldsewhere sent large amounts of money back home. In 1996 alone,
these farmers sent 680 million yuan back.
</P>
<P>
The increased revenues, in turn, helped local post and telecom
authorities to upgrade infrastructure to the tune of 15 million
yuan last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
