<HEADLINE> Sichuan Boosting Expressways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan Province
plans to build superhighways in the next four years that will link
the provincial capital of Chengdu with other cities in the south.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, a modern transport network will then be formed in
Sichuan. Cities to be connected with Chengdu are Zigong, Yibin,
Luzhou, Neijiang, and Leshan.
</P>
<P>
The provincial Planning Commission has decided to set aside
more than 14 billion yuan to build and upgrade a group of
highways, railways, sea ports, and airports. Part of the funds
will be used for expressways, local transportation authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
A batch of expressway projects has already been completed in
the past few years, including the Chengdu-Chongqing expressway and
Chengdu-Pengshan section of Chengdu-Leshan expressway, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 and 1998, southern Sichuan will have a total of 137 km
of superhighways in operation, according to a new provincial plan.
</P>
<P>
Work will begin this year on an 80-km-long expressway from
Longchang to Naxi and the Leshan-Pengshan section of the
Chengdu-Leshan superhighway, which is 87 km long. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
