<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power from Inner Mongolia Lights One Quarter of Beijing Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Inner Mongolia, which relied
heavily on Beijing for power supply only a few years ago, is now
lighting one quarter of homes in Beijing with power it generates.
</P>
<P>
Uligi, general manager of the Power Corporation of Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region, who is in Beijing attending the annual
session of the National People's Congress, attributed the progress
to the region's strategy of developing its rich natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Uligi said Inner Mongolia, which is several hundred kilometers
north of Beijing, used to rely on Beijing for electric power
supply when millions of tons of coal were waiting to be
transported to other parts of China, he said.
</P>
<P>
By now, Inner Mongolia has become an important power supply in
north China's power network, one of six such networks in China.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, he said, the region generated 31.8 billion kwh of
electricity, 12 billion kwh of which was transmitted to the rest
of the country. This means eight million tons of coal are
transported out of the region each year through power transmission
lines, he said.
</P>
<P>
As one of the major coal producers and produces, Inner Mongolia
boasts China's second largest coal reserves and produces 70 million
tons of coal annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Beat Uzbekistan in World Junior Water Polo Tourney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT, March 5 (Xinhua) -- China beat Uzbekistan 12-5 in their
first match at the World Junior Water Polo qualifying tournament
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese team were 3-4 behind due to weak defence. They
strengthened their defence line in the second period and quickened
the attacking pace to surpass their opponents 6-5.
</P>
<P>
In the third and fourth periods, the Chinese team dominated the
match and scored six more goals to wrap up the victory.
</P>
<P>
Seven teams including China, Japan, Uzbekistan, Kazakhstan,
Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Iran are participating in the
tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
