<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine House Finalizes Income Tax Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine House of
Representatives Wednesday night finalized its version on the
income tax reform and promised to pass the bill on the third and
final reading as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The income tax reform program is the last part of the country's
Comprehensive Tax Administration Package (CTRP) to be passed by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
A timely passage of the entire tax reform package is among the
requirements of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to free the
country's economy from its supervision by June this year.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Jose de Venecia promised that the lower chamber
will make a "best effort" to pass the CTRP component and submit
this to the Senate by March 13, the deadline given by President
Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Under the income tax proposal finalized by the House ways and
means committee, corporate taxpayers can choose either a 35
percent net income tax or a 15 percent adjusted gross income tax.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Exequiel Javier said the committee decided
to increase the net income tax to 35 percent from 33 percent to
approximate the rate adopted by governments in other countries in
corporate taxation.
</P>
<P>
For individual income taxation, a family of six will have a
total tax exemption of 184,000 pesos (7,022.9 U.S. dollars)
annually or 72,000 pesos (2,748 dollars) per working member and an
additional 10,000 pesos (381.6 dollars) per dependent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
