<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andean Communications Satellite to be Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Andean
communications satellite, an idea formed 21 years ago, could
become a reality this April when public and private sector
investors from Colombia, Bolivia, Ecuador, Peru and Venezuela meet
here in the Colombian capital.
</P>
<P>
The Chamber of Computer Information in Colombia announced today
that about 72 investors from the five countries had been called to
form a company. The company would launch the satellite at a cost
of 220 million U.S. dollars, including ground installations.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the investors will contribute 120 million
U.S. dollars and that international banks will provide the other
100 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "Simon Bolivar satellite system" will be in
geostationary orbit and will improve communications among Andean
countries and with the rest of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
