<HEADLINE> IOC to Review Process of Selecting Olympic Host Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GEVENA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic Committee
(IOC) will probably review the ways of cutting the number of
Olympic bidding cities, according to IOC official.
</P>
<P>
IOC vice president Dick Pound said on Wednesday the high
numbers of bidding cities made the selection process difficult.
</P>
<P>
A record 11 cities are bidding for the 2004 summer Olympic
Games. The IOC will shorten the list to four or five cities on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
All the 11 cities have been visited by the IOC's 15-member
evaluation committee. The committee has made out a report on the
advantage and disadvantage of each of the candidate.
</P>
<P>
But seven out of the 11 cities, including Cape Town, Istanbul,
Lille, Rome, San Juan, Stockholm and St. Petersburg, have
complained to the IOC that it was unfair to shorten the list of
candidates based solely on the evaluation report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
