<HEADLINE> Mayor Says Athens' Olympic Bid Supported by People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Athens' main "weapon" in its bid
to host the 2004 summer Olympic Games is the virtually universal
support for the city's candidacy from Athenians and the Greek
people in general, Athens Mayor Dimitris Avramopoulos said today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Avramopoulos, who is a member of
the committee responsible for promoting Athens' candidacy, praised
"the unity of spirit" prevailing among all parties involved in
the city's bid.
</P>
<P>
Avramopoulos expressed guarded optimism about the chances of
Athens being included on the International Olympic Committee's
(IOC) shortlist of four or five candidate cities for the 2004
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The IOC will announce the shortlist in Lausanne Friday. Cities
included on the shortlist will continue to vie for the event
until September 5 when the winner will be announced.
</P>
<P>
IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch said recently that in
addition to the necessary infrastructure, the eleven candidates
must be able to convince the selection group that the general
population backed a particular city's candidacy. 
</P>
