<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Congressmen Lash Out at NATO's Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Members of the U.S. House of
Representatives today lashed out at the U.S. government's plan to
enlarge the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"The expansion of NATO will create a new division in Europe,"
affirmed David Obey, a senior Democrat who has followed NATO
affairs for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a House subcommittee hearing, the congressman said
that NATO's eastward expansion was "an arrogant decision we will
come to regret."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton was determined to push the
expansion of the alliance into central and eastern European
countries by the year of 1999. The 16-nation alliance is to hold a
special summit in Madrid in July to start the process.
</P>
<P>
Russia, insisting that the move will threaten its security, is
strongly opposed to it. Clinton is due to meet with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin this month for a compromise.
</P>
<P>
Obey thought that there is "a grave risk" that Russian
nationalists will exploit any Russia government decision to accept
"a movement east of the military borders of NATO."
</P>
<P>
"I think that could have profoundly negative consequences in
the long term," Obey said.
</P>
<P>
The expansion, he said, will "create a more tense no-man's land
between the newly defined NATO and Russia."
</P>
<P>
Obey questioned the decision also on other grounds. He
complained that the government made the decision to enlarge NATO
without consulting with the Congress.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think the American public has been sufficiently talked
to, about this issue, so that they can make an intelligent choice
about how they feel about it," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ralph Regula, a Republican congressman, also joined the
criticism, noting that the central and eastern European countries
should enter the European Union first before joining NATO.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the hearing, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright argued for the U.S. position on the issue, saying that
"we are dealing with an entirely new world situation."
</P>
<P>
She stressed, "One of the great challenges... is to begin to
think about an entirely new way of organizing ourselves." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
