<DOCNO> XIE19970306.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Tourney Makes Women Step into Rugby Sevens Spotlight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Women's rugby is poised to step
into the international spotlight at the weekend before the
(men's) World Cup Sevens when the inaugural Jardine Fleming Unit
Trust Hong Kong Invitational Women's Rugby Sevens kicks off at
Aberdeen Stadium here.
</P>
<P>
Twelve teams from around the world including one from hosts
Hong Kong will compete from March 15 to 16 in what is considered
to be the most prestigious women's rugby tournament ever held.
</P>
<P>
Overseas teams taking part are England, which won the 1994
World Cup in the 15-a-side event, Arabian Gulf, Australia,
Canada, Fiji, the Netherlands, Japan, New Zealand, Scotland,
Singapore and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The teams have been split into two pools of six, according to
a draw held here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Rugby Football Union has formed a squad with 10
players from four clubs. "Women's rugby has been developing very
rapidly in Hong Kong and we do hope that the coming tournament
helps the sport grow even stronger," said team captain Katie
Rhymer.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old civil engineer at Hong Kong's new airport site
at Chek Lap Kok said that she had been playing rugby for six
years, three years each in Britain and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With a background for the players as engineers, college
students, marketing personnel and accountants, the team had being
training for the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
One of the fastest growing sports, women's rugby is recognized
at international level by 22 countries and regions. The Hong
Kong Invitational is the latest fixture on the women's annual
rugby calendar which also includes the Five Nations Cup and the
European Sevens.
</P>
<P>
And the event, together with the Carlsberg Cup 10s March 18-19
and the Second World Cup Sevens March 21-23, will arouse Hong
Kong with a rugby fever.
</P>
<P>
With three events in succession, "it will be the biggest 10
days of rugby ever seen," said Pieter Schats, Executive Director
of the Hong Kong Rugby Football Union.
</P>
<P>
As the center of Asian rugby, Hong Kong now has six clubs with
women's teams.  
</P>
</TEXT>
