<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tories' Pensions Scheme to Place Responsibility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Prime Minister John Major
announced today a plan to abolish the state earnings related
pension scheme and replace it with compulsory private pension
contributions.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he wanted to ensure the younger
generation had the extra security of a fund "built up in their own
names."
</P>
<P>
Such a scheme would allow people to build up their own personal
fund for their pension. The concept is in line with the Tories'
aim of increasing personal wealth and enabling people to build up
their own pool of capital assets and savings.
</P>
<P>
The scheme was approved Tuesday by a cabinet meeting. It is an
unfunded state-run pension plan, which makes payments on top of
the universal basic pension.
</P>
<P>
The Tory initiative is intended to deliver substantial public
expenditure savings over the long term, but there could be costs
to the government and taxpayers as the new system of private
provision is phased in.
</P>
<P>
The scheme would also counter Labor's vision of a
"stake-holder" society, by showing that the Tories would enable
people to have greater control over their pensions.
</P>
<P>
The Tories are anxious to trump Labor on social security, as
the opposition has promised that a Labor government would build a
"welfare and education system for the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the scheme, Labor's shadow chancellor Gordon
Brown said, "The tax and spending problems with the Conservative
pension proposals is utterly basic: there are huge front end costs
which will run into billions of pounds and mean higher taxes for
everyone."
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that the cumulative public cost of
the scheme would reach 151 billion pounds (243.3 billion US
dollars) by the year 2040 which would have to be funded through
tax rises, even without setting aside money to guarantee basic
pensions if private funds failed.
</P>
<P>
Brown accused Tory of wanting to privatize state pensions and
putting at risk basic cover for people retiring in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
