<HEADLINE> US to Donate 25,000 Dlrs for Iran Earthquake Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that it is going to donate 25,000 U.S. dollars to Iran as
earthquake relief.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns, in announcing the
donation, said Washington's problems with Tehran are "separate
with our willingness to help people in need."
</P>
<P>
Iran appealed Tuesday for international aid for victims of the
earthquake in Ardabil Province last Friday, which killed nearly
1,000, injured 2,600 and left 36,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the appeal, the United Nations reported that
U.N. agencies, Norway and Demark had pledged 515,000 dollars for
earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the money donated by the United States would not "go
to the government of Iran," but "to families of those who died and
to those who have been injured or suffered other losses." 
</P>
