<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Chiefs Consider Cuts in Fighter Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Joint Chiefs of Staff of
the United States told Congress today that they are considering
cutting one of three multibillion-dollar fighter planes or sharply
reducing the overall number of fighters the Pentagon buys.
</P>
<P>
Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston, vice chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, said the options include canceling the Air Force
F-22 fighter, the Joint Strike Fighter or the Navy FA-18 E and F
fighter, or reducing by 25 percent to 50 percent of the number of
planes the Pentagon purchases.
</P>
<P>
Another option is to go forward with all three fighter programs
over the coming decades, which would replace fighter planes that
were designed in the 1970s and are running up against competitors
that can outperform them.
</P>
<P>
Ralston said the estimated cost of the three fighter programs
would amount to 16 percent of total planned Pentagon weapons
spending and the proposed purchase of about 4,400 planes "is well
within our means."
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon will make a final decision in May when it releases
the "Quadrennial Defense Review," which will set the basic
military strategy and force structure into the next century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
