<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rebound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks rallied today
along with bond prices after Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan took a more soothing approach in delivering his
assessment of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average gained 93.13, or nearly 1.4
percent, to 6,945.85, moving back within striking distance of
7,000.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than a 5-to-3
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with its volume reaching
528.90 million shares as against 536.28 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also rose after bond prices improved,
sending interest rates lower, while Greenspan delivered the second
half of his semiannual report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 11.04, or 1.4
percent, to 801.99. The NYSE's composite index rose 4.99 to
420.67.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 11.73 to 1,329.10, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.84 to 600.88.
</P>
<P>
In a Senate appearance last week, Greenspan sent the markets
tumbling by warning for higher interest rates to contain
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Although he reiterated those points today, Greenspan was seen
as less strident in tone, suggesting that stock valuations may be
justified if company earnings forecasts prove accurate. He also
insisted today that he isn't trying to manhandle the markets.
</P>
<P>
In the bonds market, the yield on the 30-year Treasury sank
from late Tuesday's 6.86 percent, the highest finish since late
January, as low as 6.82 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Dow's biggest gainers were Boeing, Merck, DuPont, and
General Electric. Technology shares continued to show signs of
recovery from the recent profit-taking in that high-flying sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
