<HEADLINE> EU Commission Proposes Unchanged 1997/98 Farm Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
proposed mostly unchanged farm prices in 1997/98 but maintained
its demand for a 1.4 billion ECU (1.6 billion US dollar) cut in
direct aid payments to cereals and oilseed farmers.
</P>
<P>
"With some small exceptions the proposals are for a maintenance
of existing prices and market arrangements, continuing the policy
of stability which has applied since the 1992 reforms," the
commission said.
</P>
<P>
The budgetary impact of the proposals is a saving of 82 million
ECUs (94 million US dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The savings would be achieved through lower monthly increases
in intervention cereals and rice storage payments, which would be
cut in line with lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposed last summer a cut in aid payments to
cereals, oilseeds and protein crop farmers to help fund emergency
aid for beef producers hit by the "mad cow disease" crisis. The
proposal was dropped by European Union farm ministers in October.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the EU's agricultural economy in 1996, the commission
said in general terms the improvement in the economic situation of
farming in the EU continued and was even strengthened for some
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Production of cereals in 1996 is estimated at some 202 million
tons, the highest level the EU has ever achieved and some 27
million tons more than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to earlier expectations the level of sugar production
in 1996 was comparable with 1995 at 15.664 million tons.
</P>
<P>
First estimates put wine production in 1996 at around 174
million hectoliters, almost 25 million hectoliters more than in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Production of beef and veal fell by about 4 percent in 1996,
mainly because of the impact of the "mad cow disease" crisis.
</P>
<P>
Milk production in 1996 is expected to reach virtually the same
level as in 1995 (121.3 million tons). 
</P>
</TEXT>
