<HEADLINE> Zairean Gov't Endorses UN Plan, Rebels Reject Truce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko
and Prime Minister Kengo Wa Dondo have endorsed the United Nations
five-point peace plan for Zaire, Zairean Foreign Minister Gerard
Kamanda Wa Kamanda announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The peace plan, which calls for an immediate cease-fire and
withdrawal of all foreign troops from Zaire, was drafted by the
United Nations special envoy for the Great Lakes, Algerian
diplomat Mohamed Sahnoun, and adopted by the U.N. Security Council
last month.
</P>
<P>
"The president and the government of the Republic of Zaire
demand the deployment without delay of an international force of
control to make operational the peace plan of Mr. Sahnoun and the
Security Council, to verify the application in the field of the
withdrawal of all foreign troops, including mercenaries," said the
declaration of the Zairean government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tutsi-led rebel forces today again refused to
reach a cease-fire with the government forces, saying that they
wanted to hold face-to-face talks with President Mobutu first.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted Kongolo Mwenze, "minister
of justice" of the rebel alliance, as saying in the newly fallen
Zairean town of Kindu that a cease-fire should be the result of
negotiations and not a precondition of it.
</P>
<P>
"The plan of peace of the U.N. is in our favor, but to impose a
cease-fire, it is against us," he said.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan said this week that
if the warring sides of Zaire refuse to reach a cease-fire, an
international armed intervention in Zaire becomes necessary to
save tens of thousands of refugees caught in the fighting in
eastern Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
