<HEADLINE> Arafat: "Land for Peace" Principle Should Be Observed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat told the Security Council members today that "land
for peace" is the basis of the Middle East peace process and that
it should be observed.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to reporters after conferring privately with
the members of the 15-nation council a few hours before the start
of a council debate on Israel's plan to build 6,500 homes for Jews
in Eastern Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"My message today is how to implement accurately and honestly
what had been agreed upon, to prevent any provocations and
breaching of the United Nations and Security Council resolution,
which is the platform of the peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We went to Madrid according to resolutions 242 and 338 and
land for peace. This is what we are asking," he added, referring
to the 1991 conference that launched the peace process and U.N.
resolutions adopted in 1967 and 1973 that embodied the idea of
land for peace.
</P>
<P>
In similar remarks after conferring with Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, Arafat said the new Israeli settlement was an issue not
only for the Palestinians but also "for the Arabs, for the
Moslems, for the Christians." 
</P>
