<HEADLINE> Ireland to Benefit From UK EMU Opt-Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Inward investment in the Irish
Republic would continue to increase if the country decided to join
the European Monetary Union (EMU) while Britain stayed out,
according to Ireland's biggest industrial group.
</P>
<P>
Announcing a 21 percent rise in pre-tax profits Tuesday, Don
Godson, chief executive of CRH building material group, said that
Britain's decision to stay out of the first phase of the EMU might
lead to a further increase in inward investment in Ireland from
companies which will not want to operate outside the common
currency.
</P>
<P>
"Ireland has been an attractive location for companies wanting
an English-speaking base in Europe. Interest rates of just under 6
percent for five-year money and forecast inflation of 2 percent
compare very favorable with the UK," Godson said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, corporation tax of 10 percent, low labor costs and
the ready availability of a well-educated work force have been
added attractions for many foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Inward investment in Ireland has risen sharply in recent years
with the country's economic growth rates among the highest for the
countries of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development. Gross domestic product is forecast to rise by 5-6
percent this year. 
</P>
