<HEADLINE> Namibia's 1997/98 Budget Tabled in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Namibia's 1997/98 budget of
5,755 million Namibian Dollars (about 1,251 million US Dollars)
was tabled today in the National Assembly by Finance Minister
Nangolo Mbumba in the capital Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
In his budget speech, Mbumba said fiscal prudence would set
the groundwork for economic growth and prosperity of the country,
reported the South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Mbumba told parliamentarians that the proposed total
expenditure is 148 million US Dollars, a 13.4 percent rise
compared to that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, expected revenue for the period amounted to 1,130
million US Dollars, an increase of 15 percent over the 1996/97
budget, leaving an overall fiscal deficit of 121 million US
Dollars to be financed by borrowing and drawing on government
funds, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He also said the budget deficit is anticipated to be reduced
from 4.1 percent in the previous year to 3.7 percent of gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
"This achievement demonstrates our determination of reducing
government's expenditure levels at a faster rate than the revenue
collections, relative to overall economic activity," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Mbumba stressed that the composition of expenditure
has shifted slightly in favor of capital and development
expenditure, including lending and equity participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
