<HEADLINE> German Nuclear Waste Transport Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The German nuclear waste convoy
arrived at the storage depot at Gorleben, the northern state of
Lower Saxony, this afternoon, with police forcing the way past up
to 10,000 anti-nuclear protesters.
</P>
<P>
The six containers carrying 750 tons of highly-radioactive
nuclear waste from Germany and France thus completed their 58-hour
trek by rail and road from a southern German power station after
delays caused by protests.
</P>
<P>
The lead truck reached the isolated village of Gorleben with
its windscreen covered in paint after a protester lobbed a
paint-bomb at it. Earlier, police used ladders to cut down
protesters hanging on ropes strung between trees on the route of
the nuclear convoy.
</P>
<P>
Protesters wept in rage or erupted in wolf whistles as the
convoy's journey ended.
</P>
<P>
The overall nuclear transport this year took six days' time
beginning last Friday, under the shield of a 30,000 police force
-- Germany's largest police operation since World War II.
</P>
<P>
The security cost was around 66 million marks, or some 40
million U.S. dollars, compared with 46 million marks last year.
</P>
<P>
Anti-nuclear lobby in Bonn has said this serves as part of
their anti-nuclear-power strategy to drive up the nuclear price
through ceiling.
</P>
<P>
Being the country's largest single energy contributor, nuclear
power was reported to account for about 34 percent of Germany's
energy production in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Peter Haussmann today said that he saw no
reason to give up the concept of nuclear waste transport. Anyhow,
he added, this was not on the agenda of the cabinet. According to
him, another shipment of nuclear waste from France was possible
this year, although the schedule remained undecided.
</P>
<P>
Gerhard Schroeder, state premier of Lower Saxony, said after
the arrival of the nuclear convoy that more rational energy
policies should be considered so as to avoid any more such nuclear
transport.
</P>
<P>
He meanwhile praised the level-headedness and the resolution of
the police, who fulfilled their mission under "very, very
difficult conditions."
</P>
<P>
Protests over this year's nuclear transport began before the
shipment with demonstrations, disruption of train services through
sabotages of rail facilities, and stepped up later particularly in
the northern area, with people blocking railways and roads by
sit-ins, or with iron bars, tractors, barricades and even
trenches.
</P>
<P>
Police detained temporarily a total of several hundred
protesters in the whole process, during which several clashes
between police and protesters also occurred.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 10 kilometers from Dannenberg, where
the nuclear waste was unloaded onto heavy trucks Tuesday, militant
protesters at the village of Quickborn had been in skirmishes
today with police. Petrol bombs were thrown. Police also defused a
homemade bomb along the road the nuclear convoy later passed.
</P>
<P>
This morning, police used water cannons to disperse several
thousand overnight sit-inners near the exit road at the Dannenberg
railway station. More than 100 people were injured, and 38 were
temporarily detained.
</P>
<P>
The protest delayed the trucks' departure by six hours and
there were some brief stops in Gorleben as protesters were
water-blasted off roads. The 20-kilometer journey today from
Dannenberg to Gorleben took however three hours less than expected.
</P>
<P>
One demonstrator said the police had more difficulty this year
because the protest was better organized than last year and had
more support from the locals.
</P>
<P>
The anti-nuclear protest has expanded every year since the
nuclear waste transport to Gorleben began three years ago. One
critic described the event as "an annual nuclear pilgrimage that
has become part magnet for anarchic defiance of the authorities
and part token of Germans' deep concern over the perils of atomic
power." 
</P>
</TEXT>
