<HEADLINE> World Bank Supports Caribbean Environment Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank announced today
it has approved a grant agreement for 6.3 million U.S. dollars to
help Caribbean countries prepare for the adverse effects of global
climate change along their coastlines.
</P>
<P>
The grant finances a four-year project to strengthen the
region's capacity to monitor and analyze changes in climate and
sea level dynamics and to identify vulnerable areas, the
announcement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the project will develop an integrated management
and planning framework for responding and adapting to the possible
impact of adverse trends, strengthen institutions, and develop
human resources to enhance the region's capacity to cope with
global environmental change.
</P>
<P>
The grant will be managed by the General Secretariat of the
Organization of American States, it said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the grant comes from the Global Environment
Facility (GEF), created in 1991 to provide grants to developing
countries to finance projects activities to protect the global
environment. The GEF is jointly implemented by the World Bank, the
United Nations Development Program, and the United Nations
Environment Program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
