<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Chancellor Calls for Joint EU Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Austrian Chancellor Viktor
Klima indicated here today that the European Union (EU) countries
should work out an employment pact which will oblige all of them
to fight against unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after a one-day official visit
to Bonn, the new Austrian chancellor said the EU countries should
make the same commitment to combat unemployment as they do to
ensure monetary stability.
</P>
<P>
If not all EU states were obliged to fight unemployment,
migration movements might occur, "which all of us don't want to
see," Klima warned.
</P>
<P>
Klima held separate talks today with German President Roman
Herzog, Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Finance Minister Theo Waigel.
</P>
<P>
Klima told reporters that among other topics, he had discussed
with Kohl the issue of future European security policy. He
stressed his country's determination to play an active role in the
common foreign and security policies of the EU.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, he said, Austria would also take time to
think over its neutrality. His government wanted to follow the
development of the European security system first, and then submit
a report about all the possible options for Austria to parliament
in March 1998, Klima added.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that there was no reason for Austria to join
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in its present form.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Waigel, both sides agreed that the
Maastricht Treaty criteria for joining the single European
currency, the Euro, and its start-up date of January 1, 1999
should not be changed.
</P>
<P>
Waigel said that the German government would make all possible
efforts in order to meet the conditions for participating in the
Euro.
</P>
<P>
Klima, who himself until recently was the finance minister of
Austria, expressed the hope that a strong common currency in
Europe would also give an impetus to the job markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
